{"title_page": "Championship Manager 93/94", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Championship Manager 93/94\n|image = Championship Manager '93 Coverart.png\n|developer = [[Sports Interactive]]\n|publisher = [[Domark]]\n|designer = [[Paul Collyer]], [[Oliver Collyer]]\n|engine = \n|released = 17 September 1993<ref name=\"sigames\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sigames.com/softography_view.php?id=7 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030101002431/http://www.sigames.com/softography_view.php?id=7 |archivedate=1 January 2003 |title=Championship Manager 93/94 |work=SIGames.com |publisher=Sports Interactive Ltd |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n|genre = [[Sports]]\n|modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n|platforms = [[Personal Computer|PC]], [[Amiga]]\n}}\n\n'''''Championship Manager 93/94''''' refers to the second installment in the Championship Manager series of football management computer games.\n\n==New features==\nThis game improved on the original in many ways - by far the most significant change was the use of real player names for the first time. This was the one major feature which the game had lacked in comparison to its rivals.\nOther key features to be introduced in this game included the following:\n\n* A list of selected foreign-based players that could be bought\n* Much more in-match commentary\n* Injury time\n* More player awards\n* Eight different background pictures\n* Improved loading times\n* The implementation of the [[FA Premier League]]\n\n==Alternative versions==\nThe CM93/94 engine was the basis for '''''Championship Manager Italia'''''. This was a version that simulated the top two divisions of Italian football ([[Serie A]] and [[Serie B]]). There was also a 1995 seasonal update released for this game.\n\nThe ''''' 1993/94 Season Data Up-Date Disk''''' was a seasonal update disk that updated the game's database to reflect player and club changes for the 1993/94 season.\n\nThe '''''End of 1994 Season Data Up-Date Disk''''' was an end of season update disk that updated the game's database to reflect player and club changes for the end of 1993/94 season.\n\nThere was also a little-known Norwegian-language version called '''''Championship Manager Norge''''' or '''''CM Norge''''' which simulated the Norwegian League.\n\n==Trivia==\n* The ''Championship Manager '94 - End of Season Data Disk'', which was available on the [[Amiga]], contained 2 fictional players added by a couple of people who worked on the game. The players were Mark Collis and Ferah Orosco. They were a striker and a defender, respectively, for Cambridge United in Division 3 and are regarded as the first ever fictional super-players in the CM series.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Championship Manager]]\n* [[Championship Manager series]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Championship Manager}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Championship Manager 1993}}\n[[Category:1993 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Domark games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer hotseat games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Association football management video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Championship Manager 93/94\n|image = Championship Manager '93 Coverart.png\n|developer = [[Sports Interactive]]\n|publisher = [[Domark]]\n|designer = [[Paul Collyer]], [[Oliver Collyer]]\n|engine = \n|released = 17 September 1993<ref name=\"sigames\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sigames.com/softography_view.php?id=7 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030101002431/http://www.sigames.com/softography_view.php?id=7 |archivedate=1 January 2003 |title=Championship Manager 93/94 |work=SIGames.com |publisher=Sports Interactive Ltd |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n|genre = [[Sports]]\n|modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n|platforms = [[Personal Computer|PC]], [[Amiga]]\n}}\n\n'''''Championship Manager 93/94''''' refers to the second installment in the Championship Manager series of football management computer games.\n\n==New features==\nThis game improved on the original in many ways - by far the most significant change was the use of real player names for the first time. This was the one major feature which the game had lacked in comparison to its rivals.\nOther key features to be introduced in this game included the following:\n\n* A list of selected foreign-based players that could be bought\n* Much more in-match commentary\n* Injury time\n* More player awards\n* Eight different background pictures\n* Improved loading times\n* The implementation of the [[FA Premier League]]\n\n==Alternative versions==\nThe CM93/94 engine was the basis for '''''Championship Manager Italia'''''. This was a version that simulated the top two divisions of Italian football ([[Serie A]] and [[Serie B]]). There was also a 1995 seasonal update released for this game.\n\nThe ''''' 1993/94 Season Data Up-Date Disk''''' was a seasonal update disk that updated the game's database to reflect player and club changes for the 1993/94 season.\n\nThe '''''End of 1994 Season Data Up-Date Disk''''' was an end of season update disk that updated the game's database to reflect player and club changes for the end of 1993/94 season.\n\nThere was also a little-known Norwegian-language version called '''''Championship Manager Norge''''' or '''''CM Norge''''' which simulated the Norwegian League.\n\n==Trivia==\n* The ''Championship Manager '94 - End of Season Data Disk'', which was available on the [[Amiga]], contained 2 fictional players added by a couple of people who worked on the game. The players were Mark Collis and Ferah Orosco. They were a striker and a defender, respectively, for Cambridge United in Division 3 and are regarded as the first ever fictional super-players in the CM series.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Championship Manager]]\n* [[Championship Manager series]]\n\n{{Championship Manager}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Championship Manager 1993}}\n[[Category:1993 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Domark games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer hotseat games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Association football management video games]]\n", "name_user": "Starvinho", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Championship_Manager_93/94"}
{"title_page": "Upper Mustang", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Mustang, Nepal|the city in Pakistan|Mastung, Pakistan|modern district|Mustang District}}\n{{Infobox country\n| conventional_long_name                = Kingdom of Lo&nbsp;/ Mustang<br />\u0f66\u0fa8\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f4b\u0f44\n| common_name                = Upper Mustang\n| image_flag                = Flag of Mustang.svg\n| image_map    = Mustang district location.png\n| map_caption                = Location of [[Mustang District]] in [[Nepal]].\n| official_languages                = {{flatlist|{{unbulleted list |[[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]] and [[Nepali language|Nepali]]}}}}\n| area_km2                = 2,020<ref name=\"RD1998\">{{cite journal |last=Raffaele |first=Paul |title=Into the Forbidden Kingdom of Mustang |journal=Reader's Digest |date=April 1998 |volume=71 |series=421}}</ref>\n| area_sq_mi                = 700<ref name=\"RD1998\" />\n| population_estimate                = 7,000<ref name=\"RD1998\" />\n| population_density_km2                = 3.47\n| population_density_sq_mi                = 10\n| capital                = [[Lo Manthang]]\n| established            = 1380\n| religion               = [[Hinduism]]<br>[[Buddhism]]<br>[[Kiratism]]<br> [[Animism]]<br> [[Shamanism|Nepalese Shamanism]]\n| demonym                = \n| area_rank              = \n| GDP_PPP                = \n| GDP_PPP_year           = \n| HDI                = \n| HDI_year                = \n| today                = \n}}\n[[File:LoManthang 1.JPG|thumb|Lo Manthang]]\n'''Mustang''' (from the [[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]] ''m\u00f6ntang'' ({{bo|w=smon-thang}}), {{lang-ne|\u092e\u0941\u0938\u094d\u0924\u093e\u0902\u0917}} ''Must\u0101\u1e43g'' \"fertile plain\"), formerly '''Kingdom of Lo''', is a remote and isolated region of the Nepalese Himalayas. The ''Upper Mustang'' was a restricted demilitarized area until 1992 which makes it one of the most preserved regions in the world, with a majority of the population still speaking traditional [[Tibetic languages]]. [[Tibetan culture]] has been preserved by the relative isolation of the region from the outside world. Life in Mustang revolves around tourism, [[animal husbandry]] and trade.\n\nThe ''Upper Mustang'' comprise the northern two-thirds of [[Mustang District]] of [[Gandaki Pradesh]], [[Nepal]]. It consists of three rural municipalities namely [[Lo Manthang]], [[Dalome]], and [[Baragung Muktichhetra]].\n\nThe southern third of the district is called '''Thak''' and is the homeland of the [[Thakali people|Thakali]], who speak the [[Thakali language]], and whose culture combines Tibetan and [[Culture of Nepal|Nepalese]] elements. \n\nMustang's status as a kingdom ended in 2008 when its [[Suzerainty|suzerain]] [[Kingdom of Nepal]] became a [[republic]]. The influence of the outside world, especially [[China]], is growing and contributing to rapid change in the lives of Mustang's people.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/aljazeeracorrespondent/2011/10/201110912360944324.html Mustang: A Kingdom on the Edge] [[Al Jazeera]] Correspondent</ref> The development works are increasing there day by day with the higher pace.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Jigme Palbar Bista.jpg|thumb|Raja [[Jigme Dorje Palbar Bista]].]]\nMustang was once an independent kingdom, although closely tied by language and culture to Tibet. From the 15th century to the 17th century, its strategic location granted Mustang control over the trade between the [[Himalayas]] and [[India]]. At the end of the 18th century the kingdom was annexed by [[Kingdom of Nepal|Nepal]] and became a dependency of the [[Kingdom of Nepal]] since 1795<ref>https://flagspot.net/flags/np-must.html</ref>\n\nKingdom of Lo Manthang supported Tibet and the [[Qing Empire]] during the [[Sino-Nepalese War]]. \n\nThough still recognized by many Mustang residents, the [[monarchy]] ceased to exist on October 7, 2008, by order of the Government of Nepal.<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-10/08/content_10167598.htm China View news]</ref> The last official and later unofficial king ([[raja]] or ''gyelpo'') was [[Jigme Dorje Palbar Bista]] (1930\u20132016),<ref>[http://www.royalark.net/Nepal/mustang2.htm Royal Ark]</ref> who traced his lineage directly back to [[Ame Pal]], the warrior who founded this [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] kingdom in 1380.<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020421/spectrum/travel.htm Wild, windy and harsh, yet stunningly beautiful]; [[The Sunday Tribune]]; April 21, 2002</ref> Ame Pal oversaw the founding and building of much of the Lo and Mustang capital of [[Lo Manthang]], a walled city surprisingly little changed in appearance from that time period.<ref>{{cite book |last=Peissel |first=Michel |authorlink=Michel Peissel |title=Mustang - A Lost TIbetan Kingdom |origyear=1967 |edition=2nd |year=1992 |publisher=Book Faith India, Delhi |pages=227\u201331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, a shepherd in Mustang discovered a collection of 55 cave paintings depicting the life of [[the Buddha]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/international/story/0,,2072736,00.html Shepherd leads experts to ancient Buddha cave paintings]; [[Guardian Unlimited]]; May 4, 2007.</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\nUpper Mustang has a [[Geography of Nepal#Altitudinal Belts|''trans-Himalayan climate'']] which is [[Semi-arid climate#Cold semi-arid climates|cool and semi-arid]] with [[Precipitation (meteorology)|precipitation]] in the range of {{cvt|250|-|400|mm|}}. It is in the [[rain shadow]] of the [[Annapurna]] and [[Dhaulagiri]] ranges.\n\nThe Day and Night Temperature in Upper Mustang according to the months is shown below:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Month\n|Day Temperature\n|Night Temperature\n|-\n|December, January, February\n|0 to 5 \u00b0C\n\n32 to 41 \u00b0F\n|<nowiki>-25 to -20\u00b0C</nowiki>\n\n-13 to -4\u00b0F\n|-\n|March, April, May, June\n|16 to 22 \u00b0C\n\n61 to 72 \u00b0F\n|<nowiki>-6 to -2\u00b0C</nowiki>\n\n21 to 28\u00b0\n|-\n|July, August, September\n|20 to 33\u00b0C\n\n68 to 73 \u00b0F\n|<nowiki>-3 to 0 \u00b0C</nowiki>\n\n27 to 32 \u00b0F\n|-\n|October, November\n|12 to 20 \u00b0C\n\n54 to 68 \u00b0F\n|<nowiki>-8 to -4 \u00b0C</nowiki>\n\n18 to 25 \u00b0F\n|}\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe population of the whole [[Mustang District]] in 2001 was 14,981, spread between three towns and approximately thirty smaller settlements. The inhabitants are either [[Thakali people|Thakalis]], [[Gurung]] or, in traditional Mustang, primarily [[Tibetan people|Tibetan]].\n\nMost of the population of Mustang lives near the [[Gandaki River|Kali Gandaki]] River, {{cvt|2800|to|3900|m|}} above sea level. The tough conditions cause a large winter migration into lower regions of Nepal. The administrative center of [[Mustang District]] is at [[Jomsom]] ({{convert|8|km|spell=in|}} south of Kagbeni) which has had an airport since 1962 and has become the main tourist entry point since Mustang was opened to western tourism in 1992.\n\n== Geography ==\n<gallery widths=\"220\" heights=\"220\">\nTangbe, Upper Mustang.jpg|[[Tangbe]] village from above\nView on Gyakar.jpg|Gyakar village across the gorge\nKali Gandaki riverbed in Nepal's Upper Mustang.jpg|Kali Gandaki riverbed in Nepal's Upper Mustang. View from Thsele down to the Kali Gandaki river and the fields of Chusang village, with Nilgiri's steep north face.\n</gallery>\nThe main hydrographic feature of Mustang is the [[Gandaki River]]. The river runs southward towards Nepal [[Terai]], bisecting Mustang. Routes paralleling the river once served as a major trade route between Tibet and [[India]], especially for [[salt]]. Part of the river valley in the southern [[Mustang District]] forms the [[Kali Gandaki Gorge]], by some measures the deepest gorge in the world.\n\nTraditional Mustang (the Lo Kingdom) is {{cvt|53|km|||}} north&ndash;south at its longest, {{cvt|60|km|||}} east&ndash;west at its widest and ranges from a low point of {{cvt|2750|m|||}} above sea level on the Kali Gandaki River just north of [[Kagbeni, Mustang|Kagbeni]] to {{cvt|6700|m|||}} at Khamjung Himal, a peak in southeast Mustang.\n\n== Transport ==\nUpper Mustang is on an ancient trade route between Nepal and Tibet exploiting the lowest {{convert|4660|m|ft|-2|adj=on}} pass [[Kora La]] through the [[Himalaya]] west of [[Sikkim]]. This route remained in use until [[Battle of Chamdo|China's annexation of Tibet]] in 1950.\n\nMechanized access inside Nepal began with the opening of an [[Jomsom Airport|airstrip]] at [[Jomsom]] at the approximate boundary between the southern ''Thak'' and northern ''Lo'' sections of the valley, which was in operation by the 1960s.\n\nChina eventually decided to revitalize trade and in 2001 completed a {{convert|20|km|mi|0|adj=on}} road from the [[Geography of Nepal#Border crossings with Tibet Autonomous Region, China|international border]] to Lo Manthang.<ref>\n{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New highway divides isolated Buddhist kingdom of Mustang|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2007/05/19/2003361588/1 |newspaper=Taipei Times \n|location=Taipei, Taiwan|agency=AFP |date=May 19, 2007 |accessdate=Dec 14, 2013}}</ref> Across the [[Tibet Autonomous Region|TAR]] border is [[Zhongba County]] of [[Shigatse Prefecture]]. [[China National Highway 219]] follows the valley of the [[Yarlung Tsangpo River]] some {{convert|50|km|mi|0}} north of the border.\n\nMeanwhile, road-building from the south was inhibited by difficulties along the [[Kali Gandaki Gorge]] to the south, but proceeded incrementally. In 2010, a {{convert|9|km|mi|0|adj=on|spell=in}} gap remained but the road was completed before 2015 and is suitable for high clearance and [[four wheel drive]] vehicles. Currently, the easiest and only widely used road corridor, from [[Kathmandu]] to [[Lhasa]]\u2014named [[Arniko Rajmarg|Arniko Highway]] in Nepal and [[China National Highway 318]] in the TAR\u2014traverses a {{convert|5125|m|ft|-1|adj=on}} pass. This is some {{convert|465|m|ft|-1}} higher than Kora La.\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:Rigsum G\u00f6npo and prayer flags at the entrance of Samar (15842094652).jpg|thumb|Rigsum G\u00f6npo and Buddhist [[prayer flag]]s at the entrance of Samar]]\nForeign visitors have been allowed to the region since 1992, but tourism to Upper Mustang is regulated. Foreigners need to obtain a special permit to enter, costing [[United States dollar|US$]]50 per day per person. Most tourists travel by foot over largely the same trade route used in the 15th century. Over a thousand [[Western world|western]] trekkers now visit each year, with over 2,000 in 2008. August and October are the peak visiting months. On August 27, 2010, local youth leaders in Mustang threatened to bar tourists beginning October 1, 2010 due to the refusal of the Nepalese government to provide any of the $50 per day fee to the local economy. Visitation, however, continued uninterrupted beyond that date.<ref>[http://www.voanews.com/tibetan-english/news/world/Mustang-to-Bar-Tourists-to-Protest--101657173.html Mustang to Bar Tourists]</ref>\n\nMustang is rich in Buddhist culture, similar to the area of the [[Tibet Autonomous Region]] of the [[People's Republic of China]]. It is an alternate way to experience the Tibetan culture and landscape to the tours provided by the Chinese government. The Tiji festival in Lo-Manthang is another popular destination for tourists in the area seeking to experience the native culture.\n\nThe first westerner in Mustang was [[Toni Hagen]], Swiss explorer and geologist, who visited the Kingdom in 1952 during one of his travels across the Himalayas. French [[Michel Peissel]] is considered the first westerner to stay in Lo Manthang, during the first authorised exploration of Mustang in 1964.<ref>[[Peissel, Michel]] [1967]. ''Mustang, a Lost Tibetan Kingdom'', Books Faith, 2002</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n{{In popular culture|date=August 2017}}\n* British [[Tibetology|Tibetologist]] [[David Snellgrove]] visited and researched Mustang's Buddhist temples and monasteries in 1956, 1960\u201361 and 1978.<ref>{{cite book |last=Snellgrove |first=David |year=1989 |title=Himalayan Pilgrimage, a Study of Tibetan Religion by a Traveller through Western Nepal |edition=Second |url= |location=Boston & Shaftesbury |publisher=Shambhala |isbn= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n* In the book ''Merlin's Keep'', a novel by Madeleine Brent (alias of [[Peter O'Donnell]]) published 1977, Mustang is the setting for the heroine's youth and later adventures.\n* Mustang is the setting for a large part of the book ''The Kingdom'', a novel by [[Clive Cussler]] and Grant Blackwood published in 2011.\n* In the 2013 movie ''[[Planes (film)|Planes]]'' produced by DisneyToon Studios and released by Walt Disney Pictures one of the stops in Wings Across the World race is [[Nepal]] where the Planes land in Mustang.\n\n== Upper Mustang Permit ==\nYou need two permits to visit Upper Mustang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nepaltraveladventure.com/blog/upper-mustang-trekking-permit-fees/|title=Upper Mustang Trekking Permit Fee-Trek Information|date=2018-08-07|website=Blog - Global Holidays Pvt.ltd.|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\n* Upper Mustang Restricted area permit: US$500 each person for 10 days not night and the US$50 for an extra day. The permit starts from [[Kagbeni, Mustang|Kagbeni]].\n* [[Annapurna Conservation Area|Annapurna Conservation]] area Permit: NPR 2260 for foreigner and NPR226 for SAARC country. There is no limit on days for these permits.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jomsom Airport]]\n*[[Mustang Caves]]\n*[[Sonam Lhundrup]]\n*[[Tangbe]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [[Michel Peissel]] (1967). ''Mustang \u2013 A lost Tibetan Kingdom''. Dutton, New York.\n* [[Clara Marullo]] (1995). ''The Last Forbidden Kingdom, Mustang: Land of Tibetan Buddhism''. Photographs by Vanessa Schuurbeque. Charles E. Tuttle Co., Ltd., Rutland, Vermont. {{ISBN|0-8048-3061-4}}.\n* [[Peter Matthiessen]] (1996). ''East of Lo Monthang \u2013 In the Land of Mustang''. Photography by Thomas Laird. Shambhala Publications, Berkeley, Cal.\n\n==Documentaries==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130225174800/http://documentaryhive.com/lost-treasures-of-tibet/ Lost Treasures of Tibet], 2003-2-18.\n* [[Steve Chao]]: [http://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/aljazeeracorrespondent/2011/10/201110912360944324.html ''Mustang: A Kingdom on the Edge'']. [[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera Correspondent]], 2012-2-20.\n* ''The Last Lost Kingdom'', a Feature Documentary by Larry Levene.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons-inline|Mustang Kingdom}}\n\n{{Coord|29|05|N|83|55|E|region:NP_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Former monarchies of Asia]]\n[[Category:History of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Tibetan Buddhist places]]\n[[Category:Unification of Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Mustang, Nepal|the city in Pakistan|Mastung, Pakistan|modern district|Mustang District}}\n{{Infobox country\n| conventional_long_name                = Kingdom of Lo&nbsp;/ Mustang<br />\u0f66\u0fa8\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f4b\u0f44\n| common_name                = Upper Mustang\n| image_flag                = Flag of Mustang.svg\n| image_map    = Mustang district location.png\n| map_caption                = Location of [[Mustang District]] in [[Nepal]].\n| official_languages                = {{flatlist|{{unbulleted list |[[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]] and [[Nepali language|Nepali]]}}}}\n| area_km2                = 2,020<ref name=\"RD1998\">{{cite journal |last=Raffaele |first=Paul |title=Into the Forbidden Kingdom of Mustang |journal=Reader's Digest |date=April 1998 |volume=71 |series=421}}</ref>\n| area_sq_mi                = 700<ref name=\"RD1998\" />\n| population_estimate                = 7,000<ref name=\"RD1998\" />\n| population_density_km2                = 3.47\n| population_density_sq_mi                = 10\n| capital                = [[Lo Manthang]]\n| established            = 1380\n| religion               = [[Hinduism]]<br>[[Buddhism]]<br>[[Kiratism]]<br> [[Animism]]<br> [[Shamanism|Nepalese Shamanism]]\n| demonym                = \n| area_rank              = \n| GDP_PPP                = \n| GDP_PPP_year           = \n| HDI                = \n| HDI_year                = \n| today                = \n}}\n[[File:LoManthang 1.JPG|thumb|Lo Manthang]]\n'''Mustang''' (from the [[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]] ''m\u00f6ntang'' ({{bo|w=smon-thang}}), {{lang-ne|\u092e\u0941\u0938\u094d\u0924\u093e\u0902\u0917}} ''Must\u0101\u1e43g'' \"fertile plain\"), formerly '''Kingdom of Lo''', is a remote and isolated region of the Nepalese Himalayas. The ''Upper Mustang'' was a restricted demilitarized area until 1992 which makes it one of the most preserved regions in the world, with a majority of the population still speaking traditional [[Tibetic languages]]. [[Tibetan culture]] has been preserved by the relative isolation of the region from the outside world. Life in Mustang revolves around tourism, [[animal husbandry]] and trade.\n\nThe ''Upper Mustang'' comprise the northern two-thirds of [[Mustang District]] of [[Gandaki Pradesh]], [[Nepal]]. It consists of three rural municipalities namely [[Lo Manthang]], [[Dalome]], and [[Baragung Muktichhetra]].\n\nThe southern third of the district is called '''Thak''' and is the homeland of the [[Thakali people|Thakali]], who speak the [[Thakali language]], and whose culture combines Tibetan and [[Culture of Nepal|Nepalese]] elements. \n\nMustang's status as a kingdom ended in 2008 when its [[Suzerainty|suzerain]] [[Kingdom of Nepal]] became a [[republic]]. The influence of the outside world, especially [[China]], is growing and contributing to rapid change in the lives of Mustang's people.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/programmes/aljazeeracorrespondent/2011/10/201110912360944324.html Mustang: A Kingdom on the Edge] [[Al Jazeera]] Correspondent</ref> The development works are increasing there day by day with the higher pace.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Jigme Palbar Bista.jpg|thumb|Raja [[Jigme Dorje Palbar Bista]].]]\nMustang was once an independent kingdom, although closely tied by language and culture to Tibet. From the 15th century to the 17th century, its strategic location granted Mustang control over the trade between the [[Himalayas]] and [[India]]. At the end of the 18th century the kingdom was annexed by [[Kingdom of Nepal|Nepal]] and became a dependency of the [[Kingdom of Nepal]] since 1795<ref>https://flagspot.net/flags/np-must.html</ref>\n\nKingdom of Lo Manthang supported Tibet and the [[Qing Empire]] during the [[Sino-Nepalese War]]. \n\nThough still recognized by many Mustang residents, the [[monarchy]] ceased to exist on October 7, 2008, by order of the Government of Nepal.<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-10/08/content_10167598.htm China View news]</ref> The last official and later unofficial king ([[raja]] or ''gyelpo'') was [[Jigme Dorje Palbar Bista]] (1930\u20132016),<ref>[http://www.royalark.net/Nepal/mustang2.htm Royal Ark]</ref> who traced his lineage directly back to [[Ame Pal]], the warrior who founded this [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] kingdom in 1380.<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020421/spectrum/travel.htm Wild, windy and harsh, yet stunningly beautiful]; [[The Sunday Tribune]]; April 21, 2002</ref> Ame Pal oversaw the founding and building of much of the Lo and Mustang capital of [[Lo Manthang]], a walled city surprisingly little changed in appearance from that time period.<ref>{{cite book |last=Peissel |first=Michel |authorlink=Michel Peissel |title=Mustang - A Lost TIbetan Kingdom |origyear=1967 |edition=2nd |year=1992 |publisher=Book Faith India, Delhi |pages=227\u201331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, a shepherd in Mustang discovered a collection of 55 cave paintings depicting the life of [[the Buddha]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/international/story/0,,2072736,00.html Shepherd leads experts to ancient Buddha cave paintings]; [[Guardian Unlimited]]; May 4, 2007.</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\nUpper Mustang has a [[Geography of Nepal#Altitudinal Belts|''trans-Himalayan climate'']] which is [[Semi-arid climate#Cold semi-arid climates|cool and semi-arid]] with [[Precipitation (meteorology)|precipitation]] in the range of {{cvt|250|-|400|mm|}}. It is in the [[rain shadow]] of the [[Annapurna]] and [[Dhaulagiri]] ranges.\n\nThe Day and Night Temperature in Upper Mustang according to the months is shown below:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Month\n|Day Temperature\n|Night Temperature\n|-\n|December, January, February\n|0 to 5 \u00b0C\n\n32 to 41 \u00b0F\n|<nowiki>-25 to -20\u00b0C</nowiki>\n\n-13 to -4\u00b0F\n|-\n|March, April, May, June\n|16 to 22 \u00b0C\n\n61 to 72 \u00b0F\n|<nowiki>-6 to -2\u00b0C</nowiki>\n\n21 to 28\u00b0\n|-\n|July, August, September\n|20 to 33\u00b0C\n\n68 to 73 \u00b0F\n|<nowiki>-3 to 0 \u00b0C</nowiki>\n\n27 to 32 \u00b0F\n|-\n|October, November\n|12 to 20 \u00b0C\n\n54 to 68 \u00b0F\n|<nowiki>-8 to -4 \u00b0C</nowiki>\n\n18 to 25 \u00b0F\n|}\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe population of the whole [[Mustang District]] in 2001 was 14,981, spread between three towns and approximately thirty smaller settlements. The inhabitants are either [[Thakali people|Thakalis]], [[Gurung]] or, in traditional Mustang, primarily [[Tibetan people|Tibetan]].\n\nMost of the population of Mustang lives near the [[Gandaki River|Kali Gandaki]] River, {{cvt|2800|to|3900|m|}} above sea level. The tough conditions cause a large winter migration into lower regions of Nepal. The administrative center of [[Mustang District]] is at [[Jomsom]] ({{convert|8|km|spell=in|}} south of Kagbeni) which has had an airport since 1962 and has become the main tourist entry point since Mustang was opened to western tourism in 1992.\n\n== Geography ==\n<gallery widths=\"220\" heights=\"220\">\nTangbe, Upper Mustang.jpg|[[Tangbe]] village from above\nView on Gyakar.jpg|Gyakar village across the gorge\nKali Gandaki riverbed in Nepal's Upper Mustang.jpg|Kali Gandaki riverbed in Nepal's Upper Mustang. View from Thsele down to the Kali Gandaki river and the fields of Chusang village, with Nilgiri's steep north face.\n</gallery>\nThe main hydrographic feature of Mustang is the [[Gandaki River]]. The river runs southward towards Nepal [[Terai]], bisecting Mustang. Routes paralleling the river once served as a major trade route between Tibet and [[India]], especially for [[salt]]. Part of the river valley in the southern [[Mustang District]] forms the [[Kali Gandaki Gorge]], by some measures the deepest gorge in the world.\n\nTraditional Mustang (the Lo Kingdom) is {{cvt|53|km|||}} north&ndash;south at its longest, {{cvt|60|km|||}} east&ndash;west at its widest and ranges from a low point of {{cvt|2750|m|||}} above sea level on the Kali Gandaki River just north of [[Kagbeni, Mustang|Kagbeni]] to {{cvt|6700|m|||}} at Khamjung Himal, a peak in southeast Mustang.\n\n== Transport ==\nUpper Mustang is on an ancient trade route between Nepal and Tibet exploiting the lowest {{convert|4660|m|ft|-2|adj=on}} pass [[Kora La]] through the [[Himalaya]] west of [[Sikkim]]. This route remained in use until [[Battle of Chamdo|China's annexation of Tibet]] in 1950.\n\nMechanized access inside Nepal began with the opening of an [[Jomsom Airport|airstrip]] at [[Jomsom]] at the approximate boundary between the southern ''Thak'' and northern ''Lo'' sections of the valley, which was in operation by the 1960s.\n\nChina eventually decided to revitalize trade and in 2001 completed a {{convert|20|km|mi|0|adj=on}} road from the [[Geography of Nepal#Border crossings with Tibet Autonomous Region, China|international border]] to Lo Manthang.<ref>\n{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New highway divides isolated Buddhist kingdom of Mustang|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2007/05/19/2003361588/1 |newspaper=Taipei Times \n|location=Taipei, Taiwan|agency=AFP |date=May 19, 2007 |accessdate=Dec 14, 2013}}</ref> Across the [[Tibet Autonomous Region|TAR]] border is [[Zhongba County]] of [[Shigatse Prefecture]]. [[China National Highway 219]] follows the valley of the [[Yarlung Tsangpo River]] some {{convert|50|km|mi|0}} north of the border.\n\nMeanwhile, road-building from the south was inhibited by difficulties along the [[Kali Gandaki Gorge]] to the south, but proceeded incrementally. In 2010, a {{convert|9|km|mi|0|adj=on|spell=in}} gap remained but the road was completed before 2015 and is suitable for high clearance and [[four wheel drive]] vehicles. Currently, the easiest and only widely used road corridor, from [[Kathmandu]] to [[Lhasa]]\u2014named [[Arniko Rajmarg|Arniko Highway]] in Nepal and [[China National Highway 318]] in the TAR\u2014traverses a {{convert|5125|m|ft|-1|adj=on}} pass. This is some {{convert|465|m|ft|-1}} higher than Kora La.\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:Rigsum G\u00f6npo and prayer flags at the entrance of Samar (15842094652).jpg|thumb|Rigsum G\u00f6npo and Buddhist [[prayer flag]]s at the entrance of Samar]]\nForeign visitors have been allowed to the region since 1992, but tourism to Upper Mustang is regulated. Foreigners need to obtain a special permit to enter, costing [[United States dollar|US$]]50 per day per person. Most tourists travel by foot over largely the same trade route used in the 15th century. Over a thousand [[Western world|western]] trekkers now visit each year, with over 2,000 in 2008. August and October are the peak visiting months. On August 27, 2010, local youth leaders in Mustang threatened to bar tourists beginning October 1, 2010 due to the refusal of the Nepalese government to provide any of the $50 per day fee to the local economy. Visitation, however, continued uninterrupted beyond that date.<ref>[http://www.voanews.com/tibetan-english/news/world/Mustang-to-Bar-Tourists-to-Protest--101657173.html Mustang to Bar Tourists]</ref>\n\nMustang is rich in Buddhist culture, similar to the area of the [[Tibet Autonomous Region]] of the [[People's Republic of China]]. It is an alternate way to experience the Tibetan culture and landscape to the tours provided by the Chinese government. The Tiji festival in Lo-Manthang is another popular destination for tourists in the area seeking to experience the native culture.\n\nThe first westerner in Mustang was [[Toni Hagen]], Swiss explorer and geologist, who visited the Kingdom in 1952 during one of his travels across the Himalayas. French [[Michel Peissel]] is considered the first westerner to stay in Lo Manthang, during the first authorised exploration of Mustang in 1964.<ref>[[Peissel, Michel]] [1967]. ''Mustang, a Lost Tibetan Kingdom'', Books Faith, 2002</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n{{In popular culture|date=August 2017}}\n* British [[Tibetology|Tibetologist]] [[David Snellgrove]] visited and researched Mustang's Buddhist temples and monasteries in 1956, 1960\u201361 and 1978.<ref>{{cite book |last=Snellgrove |first=David |year=1989 |title=Himalayan Pilgrimage, a Study of Tibetan Religion by a Traveller through Western Nepal |edition=Second |url= |location=Boston & Shaftesbury |publisher=Shambhala |isbn= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n* In the book ''Merlin's Keep'', a novel by Madeleine Brent (alias of [[Peter O'Donnell]]) published 1977, Mustang is the setting for the heroine's youth and later adventures.\n* Mustang is the setting for a large part of the book ''The Kingdom'', a novel by [[Clive Cussler]] and Grant Blackwood published in 2011.\n* In the 2013 movie ''[[Planes (film)|Planes]]'' produced by DisneyToon Studios and released by Walt Disney Pictures one of the stops in Wings Across the World race is [[Nepal]] where the Planes land in Mustang.\n\n== Upper Mustang Permit ==\nYou need two permits to visit Upper Mustang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nepaltraveladventure.com/blog/upper-mustang-trekking-permit-fees/|title=Upper Mustang Trekking Permit Fee-Trek Information|date=2018-08-07|website=Blog - Global Holidays Pvt.ltd.|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\n* Upper Mustang Restricted area permit: US$500 each person for 10 days not night and the US$50 for an extra day. The permit starts from [[Kagbeni, Mustang|Kagbeni]].\n* [[Annapurna Conservation Area|Annapurna Conservation]] area Permit: NPR 2260 for foreigner and NPR226 for SAARC country. There is no limit on days for these permits.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jomsom Airport]]\n*[[Mustang Caves]]\n*[[Sonam Lhundrup]]\n*[[Tangbe]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [[Michel Peissel]] (1967). ''Mustang \u2013 A lost Tibetan Kingdom''. Dutton, New York.\n* [[Clara Marullo]] (1995). ''The Last Forbidden Kingdom, Mustang: Land of Tibetan Buddhism''. Photographs by Vanessa Schuurbeque. Charles E. Tuttle Co., Ltd., Rutland, Vermont. {{ISBN|0-8048-3061-4}}.\n* [[Peter Matthiessen]] (1996). ''East of Lo Monthang \u2013 In the Land of Mustang''. Photography by Thomas Laird. Shambhala Publications, Berkeley, Cal.\n\n==Documentaries==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130225174800/http://documentaryhive.com/lost-treasures-of-tibet/ Lost Treasures of Tibet], 2003-2-18.\n* [[Steve Chao]]: [http://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/aljazeeracorrespondent/2011/10/201110912360944324.html ''Mustang: A Kingdom on the Edge'']. [[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera Correspondent]], 2012-2-20.\n* ''The Last Lost Kingdom'', a Feature Documentary by Larry Levene.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons-inline|Mustang Kingdom}}\n\n{{Coord|29|05|N|83|55|E|region:NP_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Former monarchies of Asia]]\n[[Category:History of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Tibetan Buddhist places]]\n[[Category:Unification of Nepal]]\n", "name_user": "Xarly89", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated reference to Al Jazeera article, for the updated one (link changed)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Upper_Mustang"}
{"title_page": "Rickshaw", "text_new": "{{short description|Two or three-wheeled passenger cart, of Asian origin}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = \n| direction = vertical\n| header = [[Pulled rickshaw|Pulled]], [[Cycle rickshaw|cycle]], and [[auto rickshaw]]s\n| header_align = center\n| header_background = \n| footer = \n| footer_align = right\n| footer_background = \n| width = \n| image1 = JapaneseRickshaw.jpg\n| width1 = 250\n| caption1 = [[Pulled rickshaw]], Japan, circa 1897\n| image2 = \n| width2 = \n| caption2 =\n| image3 = \n| width3 = \n| caption3 = \n}}\n\nA '''rickshaw''' originally denoted a two or three-wheeled passenger cart, now known as a [[pulled rickshaw]], which is generally pulled by one man carrying one passenger. The first known use of the term was in 1879.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/rickshaw | title=Rickshaw | publisher=Merriam-Webster, Incorporated | accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref> Over time, [[cycle rickshaw]]s (also known as pedicabs or trishaws), [[auto rickshaw]]s, and [[electric rickshaw]]s were invented, and have replaced the original pulled rickshaws, with a few exceptions for their use in tourism.\n\nPulled rickshaws created a popular form of transportation, and a source of employment for male laborers, within [[Asia]]n cities in the 19th century. Their appearance was related to newly acquired knowledge of [[ball-bearing]] systems. Their popularity declined as cars, trains and other forms of transportation became widely available.\n\n[[Auto rickshaw|Auto rickshaws]] are becoming more popular in some cities in the 21st century as an alternative to [[taxi]]s because of their low cost of hire.\n[[File:Rickshaws - asakusa - japan - Oct 25 2015.ogv|thumb|250px|(video) Various rickshaws for [[tourist]]s in [[Asakusa]], [[Japan]] (2015)]]\n\n==Etymology==\n''Rickshaw'' originates from the [[Japanese language|Japanese]] word ''jinrikisha'' ({{lang|ja|\u4eba\u529b\u8eca}}, {{lang|ja|\u4eba}} ''jin'' = human, {{lang|ja|\u529b}} ''riki'' = power or force, {{lang|ja|\u8eca}} ''sha'' = vehicle), which literally means \"human-powered vehicle\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Chamberlain|first=Basil Hall|title=Things Japanese: being notes on various subjects connected with Japan for the use of travellers and others|year=1891|publisher=K. Paul, Trench, Tr\u00fcbner & Co., Ltd.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/thingsjapaneseb03chamgoog/page/n255 241]\u2013242|url=https://archive.org/details/thingsjapaneseb03chamgoog}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Origin===\nRickshaws were invented in [[Japan]] circa 1869,<ref name=\"Lu p. 348\" /><ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> after the lifting of a ban on wheeled vehicles from the [[Edo period|Tokugawa]] period (1603\u20131868),<ref>{{cite book | title=Japan | publisher=Lonely Planet | author=Chris Rowthorn | year=2007 | pages=44 | isbn=978-1741046670 | editor=Chris Rowthorn | edition=10}}</ref> and at the beginning of a rapid period of technical advancement in Japan.<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\">{{cite book | title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 | publisher=NUS Press | author=James Francis Warren | pages=[https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr/page/14 14] | isbn=978-9971692667 | year=2003 | url=https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr/page/14 }}</ref><ref name=\"Diefendorf\">{{cite book | title=Amazing . . . But False!: Hundreds of \"Facts\" You Thought Were True, But Aren't | publisher=Sterling Publishing Company | author=David Diefendorf | year=2007 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/amazingbutfalseh0000dief/page/223 223] | isbn=978-1402737916 | url=https://archive.org/details/amazingbutfalseh0000dief/page/223 }}</ref>\n\n====Inventor====\nThere are lots of theories about the inventor, with the most likely and widely accepted theory describing the Rickshaw as having been invented in Japan in 1869,<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> by Izumi Yosuke,<ref>{{cite book | title=Critical Mass: bicycling's defiant celebration | publisher=AK Press | author=Chris Carlsson | year=2002 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/criticalmassbicy0000unse/page/170 170] | isbn=978-1902593593 | url=https://archive.org/details/criticalmassbicy0000unse/page/170 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Eyewitness Top 10 Travel Guide Series: Tokyo | publisher=Penguin |author1=DK Publishing |author2=Stephen Mansfield | year=2009 | pages=84 | isbn=978-0756653675}}</ref> who formed a partnership with Suzuki Tokujiro and Takayama Kosuke to build the vehicles,<ref name=\"Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric p. 424\">{{cite book | title=Japan enciklopedia | publisher=Harvard University Press | author=Louis Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric | year=2002 | pages=424 | isbn=978-0674017535 | others=K\u00e4the Roth (translator) }}</ref> having been \"inspired by the horse carriages that had been introduced to the streets of [[Tokyo]] a few years earlier\".<ref name=\"De Mente p. 94\">{{cite book | title=The Bizarre and the Wondrous from the Land of the Rising Sun! | publisher=Cultural-Insight Books | author=Boye De Mente | year=2010 | isbn=978-1456424756 | editor=Demetra De Ment | pages=94 }}</ref>\n\nOther theories about the inventor of the Rickshaw include:\n* [[Jonathan Scobie]] (or Jonathan Goble), an American missionary to Japan, is said to have invented the rickshaw around 1869 to transport his invalid wife through the streets of [[Yokohama]].<ref name=\"Diefendorf\" /><ref>{{cite book |title=Jonathan Goble of Japan |last=Parker |first= F. Calvin |year=1990 |publisher=University Press of America |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8191-7639-4 }}</ref><ref name=\"Sobey\" />\n* An American [[blacksmith]] named Albert Tolman is said to have invented the rickshaw, or \"man drawn lorry\" in 1846 in [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]], Massachusetts, for a [[South American]] bound [[missionary]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9A4sMXVjcUC&pg=PT166 | title=Through the Heartland on U.S. 20: Massachusetts: Volume I: A Historical Travel Guide | publisher=PublishAmerica | author=William E. Lewis | isbn=978-1462624591| date=2007-03-26 }}</ref>\n* In [[New Jersey]], the Burlington County Historical Society claims an 1867 invention by carriage maker James Birch, and exhibits a Birch rickshaw in its museum.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.burlingtoncountyhistoricalsociety.org/museum.php |title=Corson Poley Center |publisher=Burlington County Historical Society |accessdate=2011-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007095954/http://www.burlingtoncountyhistoricalsociety.org/museum.php |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref>\n\nJapan historian Seidensticker wrote of the theories:\n<blockquote>Though the origins of the rickshaw are not entirely clear, they seem to be Japanese, and of Tokyo specifically. The most widely accepted theory offers the name of three inventors, and gives 1869 as the date of invention.<ref name=\"Lu p. 348\">{{cite book | title=Beyond the Neon Lights: Everyday Shanghai in the Early Twentieth Century | url=https://archive.org/details/beyondneonlights0000luha | url-access=registration | publisher=University of California Press | author=Hanchao Lu | location=1999 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/beyondneonlights0000luha/page/348 348] | isbn=978-0520215641| year=1999 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Description===\nThe vehicle had a wooden carriage that rode on \"superior Western wheels\" and was a dramatic improvement over earlier modes of transportation. Whereas the earlier sedan chairs required two people, the rickshaw generally only required one. More than one person was required for hilly or mountainous areas. It also provided a smoother ride for the passenger. Other forms of vehicles at the time were drawn by animals or were wheelbarrows.<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" />\n\nThe [[Powerhouse Museum]] in [[Sydney|Sydney, Australia]], has had a rickshaw in its collection for over 120 years. It was made about 1880 and is described as:\n<blockquote>A rickshaw, or Jinrikisha, is a light, two-wheeled cart consisting of a doorless, chairlike body, mounted on springs with a collapsible hood and two shafts. Finished in black lacquer-ware over timber, it was drawn by a single rickshaw runner.<ref name=Powerhouse/></blockquote>\n\n===Late 19th century===\n[[File:Hanoi conducteur de pp.jpg|thumb|19th century rickshaw in [[Hanoi]].]]\nIn the Late 19th century, hand-pulled Rickshaws became an inexpensive, popular mode of transportation across [[Asia]].<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> Peasants who migrated to large Asian cities often worked first as a rickshaw runner.<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95\" /><ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 37\" /> It was \"the deadliest occupation in the East, [and] the most degrading for human beings to pursue.\"<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 37\" />{{#tag:ref|In China, [[coolies]] performed rickshaw pulling. Other hard or demeaning jobs included being [[manual scavenging|night soil cleaners]] and dock workers.<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 37\" />|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n====Japan====\n[[File:Edward VIII with his staff wearing Happi 1922.jpg|thumbnail|Edward, Prince of Wales, and his staff disguised as rickshaw men during his visit to Japan in 1922. He bought the clothes himself in Kyoto.]]\nStarting in 1870, the [[Tokyo]] government issued a permit to build and sell \u4eba\u529b\u8eca\u3000(jinrikisha : rickshaws in Japanese) to the trio that are believed in Asia to be the rickshaw's inventors: Izumi Yosuke, Takayama Kosuke, and Suzuki Tokujiro. In order to operate a rickshaw in Tokyo, a seal was required from these men.<ref name=\"De Mente p. 94\" /> By 1872, they replaced the [[kago]] and norimono, becoming the main mode of transportation in Japan, with about 40,000 rickshaws in service. At that time man-power was much cheaper than horse-power; horses were generally only used by the military. Some of the rickshaws were artistically decorated with paintings and rear elevations. In this time, the more exuberant styles of decorations were banned.<ref>{{cite book | title=Tokyo from Edo to Showa | publisher=Tuttle Classics | author=Edward Seidensticker | year=2010 | pages=59 }}</ref> If the families were well-off financially they might have their own rickshaw runner. Generally, runners covered {{convert|32|to|48|km|mi}} in a day, at an average traveling speed of {{convert|8|km|miles}} per hour.<ref name=\"Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric p. 424\" /><ref name=Powerhouse>{{cite web | url=http://www.powerhousemuseum.com/insidethecollection/tag/jinrikisha/ | publisher=Powerhouse Museum | title=Japanese rickshaw | accessdate=April 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nJapanese rickshaw manufacturers produced and exported rickshaws to Asian countries and South Africa.<ref name=\"Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric p. 424\" />\n\n====Singapore====\n[[Singapore]] received its first rickshaws in 1880 and soon after they were prolific, making a \"noticeable change in the traffic on Singapore's streets.\"<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> [[Bullock cart]]s and [[gharry|gharries]] were used before rickshaws were introduced.<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 37\">{{cite book | title=Chinese Adaptation and Diversity: Essays on Society and Literature in Indonesia, Malaysia & Singapore | publisher=NUS Press | author=Leo Suryadinata | year=1992 | pages=37 | isbn=978-9971691868 | agency=National University of Singapore. Centre for Advanced Studies}}</ref>\n\nMany of the poorest individuals in Singapore in the late nineteenth century were [[poverty|poverty-stricken]], unskilled people of [[Chinese people|Chinese]] [[ancestry]]. Sometimes called [[coolies]], the hardworking men found that pulling a rickshaw was a new opportunity for employment.<ref name=\"Warren p. 15\">{{cite book | title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 | publisher=NUS Press | author=James Francis Warren | pages=[https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr/page/15 15] | isbn=978-9971692667 | year=2003 | url=https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr/page/15 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1897, [[martial law]] was declared to end a four-day rickshaw workers' strike.<ref name=\"Carlsson p. 171\" />\n\n====Other====\n[[File:Cycle rickshaw Beijing.jpg|thumb|Traditional Chinese touring cycle rickshaw in Beijing]]\nIn China, the rickshaw was first seen in 1873 and was used for public transportation the following year. Within a year there were 10,000 rickshaws in operation.<ref>Beyond the Neon Lights: Everyday Shanghai in the Early Twentieth Century</ref> Around 1880 rickshaws appeared in India, first introduced in [[Shimla|Simla]] by [[John Fordyce (missionary)|Reverend J. Fordyce]].<ref>{{ cite book | title=Imperial Simla: the political culture of the Raj | author=Pamela Kanwar | edition=2| publisher=Oxford University Press | year=2003 | page=176 | isbn=978-0195667219 }}</ref> At the turn of the century they were introduced in Calcutta, India, and by 1914 were a conveyance for hire.<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> The rickshaw was also introduced to Korea in the late 19th century.<ref>{{cite book | title=Seoul, twentieth century, growth and change of the last 100 years | publisher=\uc11c\uc6b8\uc2dc\uc815\uac1c\ubc1c\uc5f0\uad6c\uc6d0 | year=2003 | pages=164 | isbn=978-8980523054 | edition=2 | editor=Kwang-joong Kim}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\nAfter [[World War II]], there was a major shift in the use of man-powered rickshaws:\n<blockquote>Hand-[[pulled rickshaw]]s became an embarrassment to modernizing urban elites in the [[Third World]], and were widely banned, in part because they were symbolic, not of modernity, but of a [[feudal]] world of openly marked class distinctions. Perhaps the seated rickshaw passenger is too close to the back of the laboring driver, who, besides, is metaphorically a draught animal harnessed between shafts.<ref name=\"Carlsson p. 171\">{{cite book | title=Critical Mass: bicycling's defiant celebration | publisher=AK Press | author=Chris Carlsson | year=2002 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/criticalmassbicy0000unse/page/171 171] | isbn=978-1902593593 | url=https://archive.org/details/criticalmassbicy0000unse/page/171 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe [[cycle rickshaw]] was built in the 1880s and was first used with regularity starting in 1929 in Singapore. They were found in every south and east Asian country by 1950. By the late 1980s there were estimated 4 million cycle rickshaws in the world.<ref name=\"Edgerton p. 46\">{{cite book | title=The Shock of the Old: Technology and Global History Since 1900 | publisher=Oxford University Press | author=David Edgerton | year=2011 | pages=46 | isbn=978-0199832613}}</ref>\n\n====Africa====\n[[File:Tuk-tuk in Nairobi 2.JPG |thumb |right|An [[auto rickshaw]] (''tuk-tuk'') in [[Nairobi]]]]\nRickshaws were introduced to [[Durban]], [[South Africa]], and by 1904 there were about 2,000 registered rickshaw pullers.<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /><ref>{{cite web |author=Ethekwini Municipality Communications Department, edited by Fiona Wayman, Neville Grimmet and Angela Spencer |url=http://www.durban.gov.za/durban/discover/history/our-town/rickshaws |title=Zulu Rickshaws |publisher=Durban.gov.za |accessdate=2010-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100519145024/http://www.durban.gov.za/durban/discover/history/our-town/rickshaws |archivedate=2010-05-19 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book | title=South Africa: Lesotho & Swaziland | publisher=Lonely Planet |author1=Mary Fitzpatrick |author2=Kate Armstrong | year=2006 | pages=308 | isbn=978-1740599702 | edition=7}}</ref> Rickshaws operated in [[Nairobi]] in the beginning of the 20th century; pullers went on strike there in 1908.<ref>{{ cite book | title=Africa under colonial domination 1880 - 1935: 7 | editor=A. Adu Boahen, Unesco. International Scientific Committee for the Drafting of a General History of Africa | publisher=UNESCO | year=1985 | page=666 | isbn=978-9231017131 }}</ref> In the 1920s, they were used in [[Bagamoyo]], [[Tanga, Tanzania]] and other areas of [[East Africa]] for short distances.<ref>{{ cite book | title=60 Years in East Africa: The Life of a Settler | author=Werner Voigt | publisher=General Store Publishing House | pages=32, 34\u201335 | year=1995 | isbn=978-1896182391 }}</ref><ref>http://www.ezakwantu.com/Gallery%20Zulu%20Ricksha.htm</ref>\n\n====Asia====\nThe rickshaw's popularity in Japan had declined by the 1930s with the advent of automated forms of transportation like automobiles and trains. After [[World War II]], when gasoline and automobiles were scarce, they made a temporary come-back. The rickshaw tradition has stayed alive in Kyoto and Tokyo's [[geisha]] districts.<ref name=Powerhouse /><ref name=\"De Mente p. 95\" /> In the 1990s, German-made [[cycle rickshaw]]s called \"velotaxis\" were introduced in Japanese cities, including [[Kobe]].<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95\" />\n\n[[File:Hong Kong 1930s 08.jpg|thumbnail|A row of rickshaws parked near a pier in Hong Kong, circa 1930s]]\nIn [[post war]] [[Hong Kong]], rickshaws was one of the main transportation either for transporting goods or for transporting people during the Japanese invasion, known as the [[Battle of Hong Kong]]. Japanese military hired many rickshaw pullers to have them gathered and organize with other cooks and seamen for an underground armed team to enact the anti-British Colony clan. <ref>Tsai, Jung-Fang(2005). Wartime Experience, Collective Memories, and Hong Kong Identity. China Review International,2005,Vol.12(1),pp.233. http://content.ebscohost.com/ContentServer.asp?T=P&P=AN&K=19013500&S=R&D=asn&EbscoContent=dGJyMNLr40Sep7c4xNvgOLCmr1Gep7dSs6%2B4TLCWxWXS&ContentCustomer=dGJyMOzprkmzqbVMuePfgeyx44Dt6fIA</ref> However, after World War II, other forms of transport such as pedicabs and streetcar became strong competitors of rickshaws, leading the business of rickshaws into stagnation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalrepository.lib.hku.hk/catalog/5m60qt84n?locale=en|title=Des Voeux Road Central, Central District|last=Frank Owen|date=1945|website=digitalrepository.lib.hku.hk|type=Photograph|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>\n\nChiuchow men formed a faction within the Canton rickshaw pullers union in the 1920s. In addition, the Chiuchow pullers could be identified by their hats which were rounded and flat at the top; while the rival Hoklo men had a cone-shaped headgear with sharp points at the top.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=David Strand|date=June 2007|title=Reviewed Work: Reluctant Heroes: Rickshaw Pullers in Hong Kong and Canton, 1874-1954 by Fung Chi Ming|journal=The American Historical Review|volume=112|issue=3|pages=830|jstor=40006699|doi=10.1086/ahr.112.3.830}}</ref> However, it began to decline in the 1920s<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95\">{{cite book | title=The Bizarre and the Wondrous from the Land of the Rising Sun! | publisher=Cultural-Insight Books | author=Boye De Mente | year=2010 | isbn=978-1456424756 | editor=Demetra De Ment | pages=95 }}</ref>  as the new Communist government introduced the streetcar system in 1924.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Perry|first=Elizabeth|date=May 1984|title=Collective Violence in China, 1880-1980|journal=Theory and Society|volume=13|issue=3|pages=427\u2013454|jstor=657459|doi=10.1007/bf00213233}}</ref> The number of rickshaw pullers had declined from 44,200 to 25,877 six months after the opening of the tramway.<ref name=\":1\" /> It had also caused the Beijing tramway riot in October 1929.<ref name=\":1\" /> A rough form of a rickshaw is sometimes used for hauling coal, building materials or other material. Both motorized and pedal-power cycle rickshaws, or pedicabs, were used for short distance passenger travel.<ref name=\"Tiki China\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2WM23qDdOGQC&pg=PT61 | title=China Travel Guide - Tiki Travel | publisher=FB Editions | pages=PT61 | isbn=9791021306523}}</ref> There are still many rickshaws in many cities for either touring purposes (in big cities such as Beijing and Shanghai, with traditional Chinese rickshaws) or short range transportation in some counties. However, the new Communist government banned rickshaws in Canton in the early 1950s, leading to another low tide of rickshaws.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn [[Singapore]], the rickshaw's popularity increased into the 20th century. There were approximately 50,000 rickshaws in 1920 and that number had doubled by 1930.<ref name=\"Lu p. 348\" /> [[Cycle rickshaw|Cycle rickshaws]] were used in Singapore beginning in 1929. Within six years [[Pulled rickshaw|pulled rickshaws]] were outnumbered by [[Cycle rickshaw|cycle rickshaws]],<ref name=\"Edgerton p. 46\" /> which were also used by sightseeing tourists.<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 40\">Suryadinata (1992). p. 40.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Other means of transportation in Singapore are [[bus]]es, [[lorry|lorries]] and [[tram]]s.<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 40\"/>|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n[[File:Bangladeshi style Rickshaw.jpg |thumb|right|[[Cycle rickshaw]] Bangladeshi Rickshaw in Sweden.]]\nIn the 1930s, [[Cycle rickshaw|cycle rickshaws]] were used in [[Kolkata]], [[India]]; [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]]; and [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]]. By 1950 they could be found in many [[South Asia|South]] and [[East Asia|East Asian]] countries.<ref name=\"Edgerton p. 46\" /> By the end of the 20th century, there were 300,000 such vehicles in [[Dhaka]].<ref>{{cite book | title=The Shock of the Old: Technology and Global History Since 1900 | publisher=Oxford University Press | author=David Edgerton | year=2011 | pages=46\u201347 | isbn=978-0199832613}}</ref> By the end of 2013, there were about 100,000 [[electric rickshaw]]s in [[Delhi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/05/regulation-threatens-india-e-rickshaws-201451331017908658.html|title=Regulation threatens India's e-rickshaws|author=Faiz JamilFaiz Jamil|publisher=|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{further|Navdeep Asija}}\n\n====North America====\nPedicabs were introduced in North America in 1962, where they were a means of transportation at the [[Seattle]] [[World's Fair]] in the state of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Seattle's 1962 World's Fair | publisher=Arcadia Publishing | author=Bill Cotter | year=2010 | pages=55, 125 | isbn=978-0738581255}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Velotaxi1.jpg|thumb|Velotaxis in [[Nagoya, Japan]], 2005.]]\nThe 21st century has seen a resurgence in rickshaws, particularly in motorized rickshaws and cycle rickshaws. [[Auto rickshaws]], also called velotaxis, have resurged as they are about 1/3 to 1/2 the cost of regular taxis. German velotaxis are three-wheeled, powered vehicles with a space for a driver and, behind the driver, space for two passengers.<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95-96\">{{cite book | title=The Bizarre and the Wondrous from the Land of the Rising Sun! | publisher=Cultural-Insight Books | author=Boye De Mente | year=2010 | isbn=978-1456424756 | editor=Demetra De Ment | pages=95\u201396 }}</ref> [[Cycle rickshaw]]s are used in many North American, [[Europe]]an, and [[Asia]]n cities.<ref name=Sobey>{{cite book | title=A Field Guide to Automotive Technology | publisher=Chicago Review Press | author=Ed Sobey | year=2009 | pages=172 | isbn=978-1556528125}}</ref> They are increasingly being used as an eco-friendly way of short-range transportation, particularly in urban areas. Along with [[Auto rickshaw|auto rickshaws]], they are also used (particularly by Asian cities) for tourism, because of their \"novelty value as an entertaining form of transportation\". <ref name=Sobey />\n\n====Africa====\nIn Madagascar, pulled cycle and auto rickshaws are a common form of transportation in a number of cities, especially [[Antsirabe]]. They are known as ''pousse-pousse'', meaning ''push-push''.<ref>{{cite book | title=Madagascar, Volume 15 of Cultures of the World Cultures of the World - Group 15 | publisher=Marshall Cavendish |author1=Jay Heale |author2=Zawiah Abdul Latif | year=2008 | pages=75\u201376 | isbn=978-0761430360 | edition=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yNax15GoPIkC&pg=PT59&dq=pousse-pousse | title=Madagascar Travel Guide | publisher=Lonely Planet | accessdate=2013-04-13 | year=2012 | edition=7 | isbn=978-1743213018 }}</ref>\n\n====Asia====\nMacau - Still uses tri-wheels bicycle rickshaw, or Riquex\u00f3 in Portuguese, as Macau was a Portuguese colony in the past, and this kind of transportation were very famous till late 20th century, due to the fact of being a small city and few cars, not so much motorcycle, very bad public transport and none other transport such as train or subway.\nYou can go around Macau peninsula and the two island on rickshaw, and visit the Riquex\u00f3 Museum and see the evolution of rickshaw since 18th till nowadays.\n\nAutomated cycle rickshaws, called velotaxis, are popular in Kyoto and Tokyo, Japan. Their use is growing at a rate of about 20-30% a year in Japanese cities. The traditional rickshaws are still alive for travelers in some tourist places in Japan. Rickshaws are found in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95-96\" /> In China, automated and pedal-power cycle rickshaws, or pedicabs, are used for short distance passenger travel in large cities and many medium-sized cities.<ref name=\"Tiki China\" /> Most Indian cities offer [[auto rickshaw]] service; Hand-pulled rickshaws do exist in some areas, such as [[Kolkata]] (Calcutta) as a part of their transport system which also includes cycle rickshaws.<ref>{{cite book | title=Frommer's India | publisher=John Wiley and Sons |author1=Pippa de Bruyn |author2=Keith Bain |author3=David Allardice |author4=Shonar Joshi | location=2010 | pages=15, 57, 156 | isbn=978-0470645802 | edition=Fourth| date=2010-02-18 }}</ref> Sri Lanka has over 1 million auto rickshaws registered in use as of 2018.\n\n====Australia====\nIn Australia, [[Cycle rickshaw]]s or trishaws (3 wheels) are used in [[Melbourne]] and [[St Kilda, Victoria|St Kilda]]. They are also seen in [[Cowaramup, Western Australia]] at Bakehouse '38.\n\n====Europe====\n[[Image:Brighton to Newhaven along the coast 056.jpg|thumb|upright|Auto rickshaw located in [[Brighton Marina]].]]\n[[Cycle rickshaw]]s or trishaws (3 wheels) are used in most large continental European cities,<ref name=IBF /> such as:\n <!-- Australia isn't a part of Europe -->\n* Austria: [[Vienna]]\n* Denmark: [[Copenhagen]] and [[Odense]]<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A4QjqJqi7A8C&pg=PT56 | title=Denmark Travel Adventures | publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc | author=Elizabet Olesen | year=2011 | pages=PT56 | isbn=978-1588437075}}</ref><ref name=MainStreet>{{ cite web | url=http://www.pedicab.com/pedicab-operators.html | title=Main Street Pedicab Operators | publisher=Main Street Pedicabs | accessdate=April 13, 2013 }}</ref>\n* France: [[Paris]] and [[Nantes]]<ref name=MainStreet /> \n* Germany: [[Lake Constance]], [[Berlin]], [[Frankfurt]], [[Hamburg]], [[Hanover]] and other cities.<ref name=IBF>{{ cite web | url=http://www.ibike.org/economics/pedicab-intl.htm | title=Pedicabs, Cycle Rickshaws: International Directory | publisher=International Bicycle Fund | accessdate=April 13, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=MainStreet />\n* Hungary: [[Budapest]]<ref name=MainStreet />\n* Ireland: [[Cork (city)|Cork]] and [[Dublin]].\n* Italy: [[Florence]], [[Milan]],<ref name=MainStreet /> and [[Rome]]\n* The Netherlands: [[Amsterdam]] and in the [[Caribbean]], [[Willemstad]]<ref name=MainStreet /><ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.amsterdam.info/transport/bike-taxi/ | title=Bike taxi | publisher=Amsterdam Tourism & Convention Board | accessdate=April 13, 2013 }}</ref> \n* Norway: [[Oslo]]<ref name=MainStreet />\n* Poland: [[Krak\u00f3w]] and [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]]\n* Russia: [[Saint Petersburg]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greenword.ru/2012/07/velo-riksha.html|title=\u0412\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0448\u0438 \u0432 \u041f\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0435|author=pinokio|work=GreenWord.ru: \u0438\u043b\u043b\u044e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0435\u0442-\u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b \u043e \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\u0435 \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0435|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n* Spain: [[Barcelona]]<ref name=MainStreet />\n* Switzerland: [[Bern]]\n\nWithin the United Kingdom, pedicabs operate in:\n* [[London]], mostly in [[Soho]] and other areas of central London. Their activity is not regulated by [[Transport for London]], so there are no limits of the fees they can charge.<ref name=\"Edgerton p. 46\"/><ref name=MainStreet />{{#tag:ref|Rickshaws or Pedicabs as they are also known, have been operating on the streets of London for over 7 years in and around the West End, Soho, Covent Garden and Leicester Square areas.|group=\"nb\"}}\n* [[Edinburgh]], where vendors are hired like taxis and provide tours.<ref>{{cite book |  title=Frommer's Scotland |author1=Lesley Anne Rose |author2=Michael Macaroon |author3=Vivienne Crow | edition =12 | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | year=2012 | isbn=978-1119992769 }}</ref>\n* [[Oxford]].<ref name=MainStreet />\n\n====America====\n* In Canada there are pedicabs in operation in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]]<ref>{{cite book | title=Vancouver and Victoria. 4th ed. | author=Ulysses Travel Editorial Staff, Ulysses Travel Guides | publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc | year=2003 | isbn=978-2894645178 }}</ref> and [[Vancouver]]. They are regulated in [[Toronto]] and [[Vancouver]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Pedicabs, City of Vancouver | url=http://vancouver.ca/doing-business/pedicabs.aspx | publisher=City of Vancouver | accessdate=April 13, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Rickshaw owners back in driver's seat: Toronto rickshaws can now charge unlimited fares after a judge said City Hall's price limits were chosen on a \"whim.\" | url=http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/toronto/story.html?id=dad7518a-21d5-42d4-8030-d3bae4be6841 | publisher=National Post, CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. (posted on Canada.com) | date=May 9, 2007 | accessdate=April 13, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513005700/http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/toronto/story.html?id=dad7518a-21d5-42d4-8030-d3bae4be6841 | archivedate=May 13, 2013 }}</ref> Pulled rickshaw rides are available in downtown [[Ottawa]], with tours of historical [[Byward Market]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Frommer's Canada: With the best hiking & outdoor adventures |author1=Hilary Davidson |author2=Paul Karr |author3=Herbert Bailey Livesey |author4=Bill McRae |author5=Donald Olson | edition=14 | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | year=2006 | isbn=978-0470044575 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ottawarickshaws.ca/tours-and-services/downtown-rickshaw-tours/ | title=Downtown Ottawa Rickshaw Tours | publisher=Ottawa Rickshaws | accessdate=April 13, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419002430/http://ottawarickshaws.ca/tours-and-services/downtown-rickshaw-tours/ | archivedate=April 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n* In the United States, [[San Diego]] and [[New York City]] each host hundreds of pedicabs; dozens of other North American cities also have [[pedicab]] services.<ref>{{cite book | title=Proceedings of the International Conferences on Transportation Systems Planning and Operation, Volume 1 | author=Indian Institute of Technology (Madras, India). Dept. of Civil Engineering | editor=V. Thamizh Arasan |\npublisher=Allied Publishers | year=2004 | page=202 }}</ref> In New York, human powered transport is used primarily by tourists due to its cost.<ref name=\"concierge NYC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.concierge.com/ideas/hotspots/tours/500723?page=1|title=Travel Inspiration|work=Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"amny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amny.com/urbanite-1.812039/pedicab-driving-no-easy-ride-1.1293582|title=New York City News: Latest Headlines, Videos & Pictures|work=am New York|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|At a rate of $5 plus $1 per block ''per person,'' a 20-block (one mile) pedicab ride for two people will cost $50.<ref name=\"concierge NYC\" /><ref name=amny /> In a taxicab, the same ride would cost under $10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/tlc/html/passenger/taxicab_rate.shtml|title=NYC Taxi & Limousine Commission - RATE OF FARE|publisher=|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref> According to Peter Meitzler of New York's Manhattan Rickshaw Company, a passenger has an entirely different urban experience when one rides in a rickshaw.<ref>[http://www.smithsonianmagazine.com/issues/2007/march/rickshaw.php \"Rickshaws Reinvented - The ancient transportation takes a modern turn\"], Dina Modianot-Fox, Smithsonian Magazine, March 2007</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} In [[New Orleans]], pedicabs have been utilized to transport [[French Quarter]] tourists since the summer of 2012.<ref name=\"Big Breezy Pedaling: The New Orleans Pedicab\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gonola.com/2012/07/06/big-breezy-pedaling-the-new-orleans-pedicab.html|title=Big Breezy Pedaling: The New Orleans Pedicab|work=GoNOLA.com|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n* In Mexico there are thousands of pedicabs. All drivers are  in informal circumstances, and have precarious working conditions, long hours (11.3 hours a day), low wages (US$59.18 per week), and no social protections or benefits. 6.3% reported suffering from a disease, 49.5% corresponded to musculoskeletal conditions and only 11.6% were affiliated to any health system. 53.8% are owners of the vehicle and, although it does not seem to influence physical illness (P=0.03), it is related to the psychosocial ones (P=0.260).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berrones-Sanz|first=Luis David|title=The working conditions of motorcycle taxi drivers in Tl\u00e1huac, Mexico City|journal=Journal of Transport & Health|volume=8|pages=73\u201380|doi=10.1016/j.jth.2017.04.008|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|Rickshaws in the United States}}\n\n==Types==\n{{Commons category|Rickshaws}}\n{{wiktionary}}\nTypes of rickshaws include:\n* a [[pulled rickshaw]]; a two-wheeled passenger cart pulled by a human runner\n* a [[cycle rickshaw]], also called a ''pedicab''\n* an [[auto rickshaw]], also called a ''tuk-tuk, auto,  mototaxi,'' or ''baby taxi''\n* an [[electric rickshaw]], also called ''e-rickshaw''.\n\n<gallery widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:Pousse-pousse_Madagascar.jpg|Pulled rickshaw, [[Madagascar]]\nFile:Riksaw nepal.jpg|Cycle rickshaws, [[Nepal]]\nFile:Auto_Rickshaw_in_San_Francisco.jpg|Auto rickshaw, [[San Francisco, California]]\nFile:Human.rickshaw.kolkata.india.JPG|Pulled Rickshaw in [[Kolkata]]\nFile:Gem_prince.jpg|[[Fibre-reinforced plastic|FRP]],GEM e-rickshaw [[Haryana, India]]\nFile:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Becaks bij de Britse ambassade TMnr 20018038.jpg|[[Cycle rickshaw]] in [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]] known as ''\"Bechak\"''\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-break}}\n;Rickshaws\n* [[Auto rickshaw]]\n* [[Cycle rickshaw]]\n* [[Electric rickshaw]]\n* [[Pulled rickshaw]]\n* [[Rickshaw art]]\n\nDesigner\n* [[George Bliss (pedicab designer)]]\n\n{{col-break}}\n;Other human powered transport\n* [[Bath chair]]\n* [[Human-powered transport]]\n* [[Boda-boda]] (bicycle taxi)\n* [[Bicycle trailer]]\n* [[Freight bicycle]]\n* [[Quadracycle]]\n* [[Utility cycling]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{ cite book | title= Calcutta cycle-rickshaw pullers: a sociological study | author= Bandyopadhyay, Subir | publisher=Minerva Associates Publications | year=1990 | isbn=978-8185195278 }}\n* {{ cite book | title=Reluctant Heroes: Richshaw Pullers in Hong Kong And Canton, 1874-1954 | author = Fung, Chi Ming |agency=Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland | publisher=Hong Kong University Press | year=2005 | isbn=978-9622097346 }}\n* {{ cite book | title=A socio-economic survey of rickshaw drivers in Hyderabad City area | author=Indian Institute of Economics | publisher=A.P. | year=1962 }}\n* {{cite book | title=Solar-assisted Electric Auto Rickshaw Three Wheeler | author = Mulhall, Priscilla | publisher=Illinois Institute of Technology | year= 2010 }}\n* {{cite book | title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 | publisher=NUS Press | author=Warren, James Francis | isbn=978-9971692667 | year=2003 | url=https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr }}\n\n{{human-powered vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Human-powered vehicles]]\n[[Category:Japanese inventions]]\n[[Category:Rickshaws]]\n[[Category:Vehicles for hire]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Two or three-wheeled passenger cart, of Asian origin}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = \n| direction = vertical\n| header = [[Pulled rickshaw|Pulled]], [[Cycle rickshaw|cycle]], and [[auto rickshaw]]s\n| header_align = center\n| header_background = \n| footer = \n| footer_align = right\n| footer_background = \n| width = \n| image1 = JapaneseRickshaw.jpg\n| width1 = 250\n| caption1 = [[Pulled rickshaw]], Japan, circa 1897\n| image2 = \n| width2 = \n| caption2 =\n| image3 = \n| width3 = \n| caption3 = \n}}\n\nA '''rickshaw''' originally denoted a two or three-wheeled passenger cart, now known as a [[pulled rickshaw]], which is generally pulled by one man carrying one passenger. The first known use of the term was in 1879.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/rickshaw | title=Rickshaw | publisher=Merriam-Webster, Incorporated | accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref> Over time, [[cycle rickshaw]]s (also known as pedicabs or trishaws), [[auto rickshaw]]s, and [[electric rickshaw]]s were invented, and have replaced the original pulled rickshaws, with a few exceptions for their use in tourism.\n\nPulled rickshaws created a popular form of transportation, and a source of employment for male laborers, within [[Asia]]n cities in the 19th century. Their appearance was related to newly acquired knowledge of [[ball-bearing]] systems. Their popularity declined as cars, trains and other forms of transportation became widely available.\n\n[[Auto rickshaw|Auto rickshaws]] are becoming more popular in some cities in the 21st century as an alternative to [[taxi]]s because of their low cost.\n[[File:Rickshaws - asakusa - japan - Oct 25 2015.ogv|thumb|250px|(video) Various rickshaws for [[tourist]]s in [[Asakusa]], [[Japan]] (2015)]]\n\n==Etymology==\n''Rickshaw'' originates from the [[Japanese language|Japanese]] word ''jinrikisha'' ({{lang|ja|\u4eba\u529b\u8eca}}, {{lang|ja|\u4eba}} ''jin'' = human, {{lang|ja|\u529b}} ''riki'' = power or force, {{lang|ja|\u8eca}} ''sha'' = vehicle), which literally means \"human-powered vehicle\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Chamberlain|first=Basil Hall|title=Things Japanese: being notes on various subjects connected with Japan for the use of travellers and others|year=1891|publisher=K. Paul, Trench, Tr\u00fcbner & Co., Ltd.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/thingsjapaneseb03chamgoog/page/n255 241]\u2013242|url=https://archive.org/details/thingsjapaneseb03chamgoog}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Origin===\nRickshaws were invented in [[Japan]] circa 1869,<ref name=\"Lu p. 348\" /><ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> after the lifting of a ban on wheeled vehicles from the [[Edo period|Tokugawa]] period (1603\u20131868),<ref>{{cite book | title=Japan | publisher=Lonely Planet | author=Chris Rowthorn | year=2007 | pages=44 | isbn=978-1741046670 | editor=Chris Rowthorn | edition=10}}</ref> and at the beginning of a rapid period of technical advancement in Japan.<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\">{{cite book | title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 | publisher=NUS Press | author=James Francis Warren | pages=[https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr/page/14 14] | isbn=978-9971692667 | year=2003 | url=https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr/page/14 }}</ref><ref name=\"Diefendorf\">{{cite book | title=Amazing . . . But False!: Hundreds of \"Facts\" You Thought Were True, But Aren't | publisher=Sterling Publishing Company | author=David Diefendorf | year=2007 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/amazingbutfalseh0000dief/page/223 223] | isbn=978-1402737916 | url=https://archive.org/details/amazingbutfalseh0000dief/page/223 }}</ref>\n\n====Inventor====\nThere are lots of theories about the inventor, with the most likely and widely accepted theory describing the Rickshaw as having been invented in Japan in 1869,<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> by Izumi Yosuke,<ref>{{cite book | title=Critical Mass: bicycling's defiant celebration | publisher=AK Press | author=Chris Carlsson | year=2002 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/criticalmassbicy0000unse/page/170 170] | isbn=978-1902593593 | url=https://archive.org/details/criticalmassbicy0000unse/page/170 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Eyewitness Top 10 Travel Guide Series: Tokyo | publisher=Penguin |author1=DK Publishing |author2=Stephen Mansfield | year=2009 | pages=84 | isbn=978-0756653675}}</ref> who formed a partnership with Suzuki Tokujiro and Takayama Kosuke to build the vehicles,<ref name=\"Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric p. 424\">{{cite book | title=Japan enciklopedia | publisher=Harvard University Press | author=Louis Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric | year=2002 | pages=424 | isbn=978-0674017535 | others=K\u00e4the Roth (translator) }}</ref> having been \"inspired by the horse carriages that had been introduced to the streets of [[Tokyo]] a few years earlier\".<ref name=\"De Mente p. 94\">{{cite book | title=The Bizarre and the Wondrous from the Land of the Rising Sun! | publisher=Cultural-Insight Books | author=Boye De Mente | year=2010 | isbn=978-1456424756 | editor=Demetra De Ment | pages=94 }}</ref>\n\nOther theories about the inventor of the Rickshaw include:\n* [[Jonathan Scobie]] (or Jonathan Goble), an American missionary to Japan, is said to have invented the rickshaw around 1869 to transport his invalid wife through the streets of [[Yokohama]].<ref name=\"Diefendorf\" /><ref>{{cite book |title=Jonathan Goble of Japan |last=Parker |first= F. Calvin |year=1990 |publisher=University Press of America |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8191-7639-4 }}</ref><ref name=\"Sobey\" />\n* An American [[blacksmith]] named Albert Tolman is said to have invented the rickshaw, or \"man drawn lorry\" in 1846 in [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]], Massachusetts, for a [[South American]] bound [[missionary]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9A4sMXVjcUC&pg=PT166 | title=Through the Heartland on U.S. 20: Massachusetts: Volume I: A Historical Travel Guide | publisher=PublishAmerica | author=William E. Lewis | isbn=978-1462624591| date=2007-03-26 }}</ref>\n* In [[New Jersey]], the Burlington County Historical Society claims an 1867 invention by carriage maker James Birch, and exhibits a Birch rickshaw in its museum.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.burlingtoncountyhistoricalsociety.org/museum.php |title=Corson Poley Center |publisher=Burlington County Historical Society |accessdate=2011-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007095954/http://www.burlingtoncountyhistoricalsociety.org/museum.php |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref>\n\nJapan historian Seidensticker wrote of the theories:\n<blockquote>Though the origins of the rickshaw are not entirely clear, they seem to be Japanese, and of Tokyo specifically. The most widely accepted theory offers the name of three inventors, and gives 1869 as the date of invention.<ref name=\"Lu p. 348\">{{cite book | title=Beyond the Neon Lights: Everyday Shanghai in the Early Twentieth Century | url=https://archive.org/details/beyondneonlights0000luha | url-access=registration | publisher=University of California Press | author=Hanchao Lu | location=1999 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/beyondneonlights0000luha/page/348 348] | isbn=978-0520215641| year=1999 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Description===\nThe vehicle had a wooden carriage that rode on \"superior Western wheels\" and was a dramatic improvement over earlier modes of transportation. Whereas the earlier sedan chairs required two people, the rickshaw generally only required one. More than one person was required for hilly or mountainous areas. It also provided a smoother ride for the passenger. Other forms of vehicles at the time were drawn by animals or were wheelbarrows.<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" />\n\nThe [[Powerhouse Museum]] in [[Sydney|Sydney, Australia]], has had a rickshaw in its collection for over 120 years. It was made about 1880 and is described as:\n<blockquote>A rickshaw, or Jinrikisha, is a light, two-wheeled cart consisting of a doorless, chairlike body, mounted on springs with a collapsible hood and two shafts. Finished in black lacquer-ware over timber, it was drawn by a single rickshaw runner.<ref name=Powerhouse/></blockquote>\n\n===Late 19th century===\n[[File:Hanoi conducteur de pp.jpg|thumb|19th century rickshaw in [[Hanoi]].]]\nIn the Late 19th century, hand-pulled Rickshaws became an inexpensive, popular mode of transportation across [[Asia]].<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> Peasants who migrated to large Asian cities often worked first as a rickshaw runner.<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95\" /><ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 37\" /> It was \"the deadliest occupation in the East, [and] the most degrading for human beings to pursue.\"<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 37\" />{{#tag:ref|In China, [[coolies]] performed rickshaw pulling. Other hard or demeaning jobs included being [[manual scavenging|night soil cleaners]] and dock workers.<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 37\" />|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n====Japan====\n[[File:Edward VIII with his staff wearing Happi 1922.jpg|thumbnail|Edward, Prince of Wales, and his staff disguised as rickshaw men during his visit to Japan in 1922. He bought the clothes himself in Kyoto.]]\nStarting in 1870, the [[Tokyo]] government issued a permit to build and sell \u4eba\u529b\u8eca\u3000(jinrikisha : rickshaws in Japanese) to the trio that are believed in Asia to be the rickshaw's inventors: Izumi Yosuke, Takayama Kosuke, and Suzuki Tokujiro. In order to operate a rickshaw in Tokyo, a seal was required from these men.<ref name=\"De Mente p. 94\" /> By 1872, they replaced the [[kago]] and norimono, becoming the main mode of transportation in Japan, with about 40,000 rickshaws in service. At that time man-power was much cheaper than horse-power; horses were generally only used by the military. Some of the rickshaws were artistically decorated with paintings and rear elevations. In this time, the more exuberant styles of decorations were banned.<ref>{{cite book | title=Tokyo from Edo to Showa | publisher=Tuttle Classics | author=Edward Seidensticker | year=2010 | pages=59 }}</ref> If the families were well-off financially they might have their own rickshaw runner. Generally, runners covered {{convert|32|to|48|km|mi}} in a day, at an average traveling speed of {{convert|8|km|miles}} per hour.<ref name=\"Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric p. 424\" /><ref name=Powerhouse>{{cite web | url=http://www.powerhousemuseum.com/insidethecollection/tag/jinrikisha/ | publisher=Powerhouse Museum | title=Japanese rickshaw | accessdate=April 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nJapanese rickshaw manufacturers produced and exported rickshaws to Asian countries and South Africa.<ref name=\"Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric p. 424\" />\n\n====Singapore====\n[[Singapore]] received its first rickshaws in 1880 and soon after they were prolific, making a \"noticeable change in the traffic on Singapore's streets.\"<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> [[Bullock cart]]s and [[gharry|gharries]] were used before rickshaws were introduced.<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 37\">{{cite book | title=Chinese Adaptation and Diversity: Essays on Society and Literature in Indonesia, Malaysia & Singapore | publisher=NUS Press | author=Leo Suryadinata | year=1992 | pages=37 | isbn=978-9971691868 | agency=National University of Singapore. Centre for Advanced Studies}}</ref>\n\nMany of the poorest individuals in Singapore in the late nineteenth century were [[poverty|poverty-stricken]], unskilled people of [[Chinese people|Chinese]] [[ancestry]]. Sometimes called [[coolies]], the hardworking men found that pulling a rickshaw was a new opportunity for employment.<ref name=\"Warren p. 15\">{{cite book | title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 | publisher=NUS Press | author=James Francis Warren | pages=[https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr/page/15 15] | isbn=978-9971692667 | year=2003 | url=https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr/page/15 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1897, [[martial law]] was declared to end a four-day rickshaw workers' strike.<ref name=\"Carlsson p. 171\" />\n\n====Other====\n[[File:Cycle rickshaw Beijing.jpg|thumb|Traditional Chinese touring cycle rickshaw in Beijing]]\nIn China, the rickshaw was first seen in 1873 and was used for public transportation the following year. Within a year there were 10,000 rickshaws in operation.<ref>Beyond the Neon Lights: Everyday Shanghai in the Early Twentieth Century</ref> Around 1880 rickshaws appeared in India, first introduced in [[Shimla|Simla]] by [[John Fordyce (missionary)|Reverend J. Fordyce]].<ref>{{ cite book | title=Imperial Simla: the political culture of the Raj | author=Pamela Kanwar | edition=2| publisher=Oxford University Press | year=2003 | page=176 | isbn=978-0195667219 }}</ref> At the turn of the century they were introduced in Calcutta, India, and by 1914 were a conveyance for hire.<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /> The rickshaw was also introduced to Korea in the late 19th century.<ref>{{cite book | title=Seoul, twentieth century, growth and change of the last 100 years | publisher=\uc11c\uc6b8\uc2dc\uc815\uac1c\ubc1c\uc5f0\uad6c\uc6d0 | year=2003 | pages=164 | isbn=978-8980523054 | edition=2 | editor=Kwang-joong Kim}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\nAfter [[World War II]], there was a major shift in the use of man-powered rickshaws:\n<blockquote>Hand-[[pulled rickshaw]]s became an embarrassment to modernizing urban elites in the [[Third World]], and were widely banned, in part because they were symbolic, not of modernity, but of a [[feudal]] world of openly marked class distinctions. Perhaps the seated rickshaw passenger is too close to the back of the laboring driver, who, besides, is metaphorically a draught animal harnessed between shafts.<ref name=\"Carlsson p. 171\">{{cite book | title=Critical Mass: bicycling's defiant celebration | publisher=AK Press | author=Chris Carlsson | year=2002 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/criticalmassbicy0000unse/page/171 171] | isbn=978-1902593593 | url=https://archive.org/details/criticalmassbicy0000unse/page/171 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe [[cycle rickshaw]] was built in the 1880s and was first used with regularity starting in 1929 in Singapore. They were found in every south and east Asian country by 1950. By the late 1980s there were estimated 4 million cycle rickshaws in the world.<ref name=\"Edgerton p. 46\">{{cite book | title=The Shock of the Old: Technology and Global History Since 1900 | publisher=Oxford University Press | author=David Edgerton | year=2011 | pages=46 | isbn=978-0199832613}}</ref>\n\n====Africa====\n[[File:Tuk-tuk in Nairobi 2.JPG |thumb |right|An [[auto rickshaw]] (''tuk-tuk'') in [[Nairobi]]]]\nRickshaws were introduced to [[Durban]], [[South Africa]], and by 1904 there were about 2,000 registered rickshaw pullers.<ref name=\"Warren p. 14\" /><ref>{{cite web |author=Ethekwini Municipality Communications Department, edited by Fiona Wayman, Neville Grimmet and Angela Spencer |url=http://www.durban.gov.za/durban/discover/history/our-town/rickshaws |title=Zulu Rickshaws |publisher=Durban.gov.za |accessdate=2010-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100519145024/http://www.durban.gov.za/durban/discover/history/our-town/rickshaws |archivedate=2010-05-19 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book | title=South Africa: Lesotho & Swaziland | publisher=Lonely Planet |author1=Mary Fitzpatrick |author2=Kate Armstrong | year=2006 | pages=308 | isbn=978-1740599702 | edition=7}}</ref> Rickshaws operated in [[Nairobi]] in the beginning of the 20th century; pullers went on strike there in 1908.<ref>{{ cite book | title=Africa under colonial domination 1880 - 1935: 7 | editor=A. Adu Boahen, Unesco. International Scientific Committee for the Drafting of a General History of Africa | publisher=UNESCO | year=1985 | page=666 | isbn=978-9231017131 }}</ref> In the 1920s, they were used in [[Bagamoyo]], [[Tanga, Tanzania]] and other areas of [[East Africa]] for short distances.<ref>{{ cite book | title=60 Years in East Africa: The Life of a Settler | author=Werner Voigt | publisher=General Store Publishing House | pages=32, 34\u201335 | year=1995 | isbn=978-1896182391 }}</ref><ref>http://www.ezakwantu.com/Gallery%20Zulu%20Ricksha.htm</ref>\n\n====Asia====\nThe rickshaw's popularity in Japan had declined by the 1930s with the advent of automated forms of transportation like automobiles and trains. After [[World War II]], when gasoline and automobiles were scarce, they made a temporary come-back. The rickshaw tradition has stayed alive in Kyoto and Tokyo's [[geisha]] districts.<ref name=Powerhouse /><ref name=\"De Mente p. 95\" /> In the 1990s, German-made [[cycle rickshaw]]s called \"velotaxis\" were introduced in Japanese cities, including [[Kobe]].<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95\" />\n\n[[File:Hong Kong 1930s 08.jpg|thumbnail|A row of rickshaws parked near a pier in Hong Kong, circa 1930s]]\nIn [[post war]] [[Hong Kong]], rickshaws was one of the main transportation either for transporting goods or for transporting people during the Japanese invasion, known as the [[Battle of Hong Kong]]. Japanese military hired many rickshaw pullers to have them gathered and organize with other cooks and seamen for an underground armed team to enact the anti-British Colony clan. <ref>Tsai, Jung-Fang(2005). Wartime Experience, Collective Memories, and Hong Kong Identity. China Review International,2005,Vol.12(1),pp.233. http://content.ebscohost.com/ContentServer.asp?T=P&P=AN&K=19013500&S=R&D=asn&EbscoContent=dGJyMNLr40Sep7c4xNvgOLCmr1Gep7dSs6%2B4TLCWxWXS&ContentCustomer=dGJyMOzprkmzqbVMuePfgeyx44Dt6fIA</ref> However, after World War II, other forms of transport such as pedicabs and streetcar became strong competitors of rickshaws, leading the business of rickshaws into stagnation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalrepository.lib.hku.hk/catalog/5m60qt84n?locale=en|title=Des Voeux Road Central, Central District|last=Frank Owen|date=1945|website=digitalrepository.lib.hku.hk|type=Photograph|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>\n\nChiuchow men formed a faction within the Canton rickshaw pullers union in the 1920s. In addition, the Chiuchow pullers could be identified by their hats which were rounded and flat at the top; while the rival Hoklo men had a cone-shaped headgear with sharp points at the top.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=David Strand|date=June 2007|title=Reviewed Work: Reluctant Heroes: Rickshaw Pullers in Hong Kong and Canton, 1874-1954 by Fung Chi Ming|journal=The American Historical Review|volume=112|issue=3|pages=830|jstor=40006699|doi=10.1086/ahr.112.3.830}}</ref> However, it began to decline in the 1920s<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95\">{{cite book | title=The Bizarre and the Wondrous from the Land of the Rising Sun! | publisher=Cultural-Insight Books | author=Boye De Mente | year=2010 | isbn=978-1456424756 | editor=Demetra De Ment | pages=95 }}</ref>  as the new Communist government introduced the streetcar system in 1924.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Perry|first=Elizabeth|date=May 1984|title=Collective Violence in China, 1880-1980|journal=Theory and Society|volume=13|issue=3|pages=427\u2013454|jstor=657459|doi=10.1007/bf00213233}}</ref> The number of rickshaw pullers had declined from 44,200 to 25,877 six months after the opening of the tramway.<ref name=\":1\" /> It had also caused the Beijing tramway riot in October 1929.<ref name=\":1\" /> A rough form of a rickshaw is sometimes used for hauling coal, building materials or other material. Both motorized and pedal-power cycle rickshaws, or pedicabs, were used for short distance passenger travel.<ref name=\"Tiki China\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2WM23qDdOGQC&pg=PT61 | title=China Travel Guide - Tiki Travel | publisher=FB Editions | pages=PT61 | isbn=9791021306523}}</ref> There are still many rickshaws in many cities for either touring purposes (in big cities such as Beijing and Shanghai, with traditional Chinese rickshaws) or short range transportation in some counties. However, the new Communist government banned rickshaws in Canton in the early 1950s, leading to another low tide of rickshaws.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn [[Singapore]], the rickshaw's popularity increased into the 20th century. There were approximately 50,000 rickshaws in 1920 and that number had doubled by 1930.<ref name=\"Lu p. 348\" /> [[Cycle rickshaw|Cycle rickshaws]] were used in Singapore beginning in 1929. Within six years [[Pulled rickshaw|pulled rickshaws]] were outnumbered by [[Cycle rickshaw|cycle rickshaws]],<ref name=\"Edgerton p. 46\" /> which were also used by sightseeing tourists.<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 40\">Suryadinata (1992). p. 40.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Other means of transportation in Singapore are [[bus]]es, [[lorry|lorries]] and [[tram]]s.<ref name=\"Suryadinata p. 40\"/>|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n[[File:Bangladeshi style Rickshaw.jpg |thumb|right|[[Cycle rickshaw]] Bangladeshi Rickshaw in Sweden.]]\nIn the 1930s, [[Cycle rickshaw|cycle rickshaws]] were used in [[Kolkata]], [[India]]; [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]]; and [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]]. By 1950 they could be found in many [[South Asia|South]] and [[East Asia|East Asian]] countries.<ref name=\"Edgerton p. 46\" /> By the end of the 20th century, there were 300,000 such vehicles in [[Dhaka]].<ref>{{cite book | title=The Shock of the Old: Technology and Global History Since 1900 | publisher=Oxford University Press | author=David Edgerton | year=2011 | pages=46\u201347 | isbn=978-0199832613}}</ref> By the end of 2013, there were about 100,000 [[electric rickshaw]]s in [[Delhi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/05/regulation-threatens-india-e-rickshaws-201451331017908658.html|title=Regulation threatens India's e-rickshaws|author=Faiz JamilFaiz Jamil|publisher=|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{further|Navdeep Asija}}\n\n====North America====\nPedicabs were introduced in North America in 1962, where they were a means of transportation at the [[Seattle]] [[World's Fair]] in the state of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Seattle's 1962 World's Fair | publisher=Arcadia Publishing | author=Bill Cotter | year=2010 | pages=55, 125 | isbn=978-0738581255}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Velotaxi1.jpg|thumb|Velotaxis in [[Nagoya, Japan]], 2005.]]\nThe 21st century has seen a resurgence in rickshaws, particularly in motorized rickshaws and cycle rickshaws. [[Auto rickshaws]], also called velotaxis, have resurged as they are about 1/3 to 1/2 the cost of regular taxis. German velotaxis are three-wheeled, powered vehicles with a space for a driver and, behind the driver, space for two passengers.<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95-96\">{{cite book | title=The Bizarre and the Wondrous from the Land of the Rising Sun! | publisher=Cultural-Insight Books | author=Boye De Mente | year=2010 | isbn=978-1456424756 | editor=Demetra De Ment | pages=95\u201396 }}</ref> [[Cycle rickshaw]]s are used in many North American, [[Europe]]an, and [[Asia]]n cities.<ref name=Sobey>{{cite book | title=A Field Guide to Automotive Technology | publisher=Chicago Review Press | author=Ed Sobey | year=2009 | pages=172 | isbn=978-1556528125}}</ref> They are increasingly being used as an eco-friendly way of short-range transportation, particularly in urban areas. Along with [[Auto rickshaw|auto rickshaws]], they are also used (particularly by Asian cities) for tourism, because of their \"novelty value as an entertaining form of transportation\". <ref name=Sobey />\n\n====Africa====\nIn Madagascar, pulled cycle and auto rickshaws are a common form of transportation in a number of cities, especially [[Antsirabe]]. They are known as ''pousse-pousse'', meaning ''push-push''.<ref>{{cite book | title=Madagascar, Volume 15 of Cultures of the World Cultures of the World - Group 15 | publisher=Marshall Cavendish |author1=Jay Heale |author2=Zawiah Abdul Latif | year=2008 | pages=75\u201376 | isbn=978-0761430360 | edition=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yNax15GoPIkC&pg=PT59&dq=pousse-pousse | title=Madagascar Travel Guide | publisher=Lonely Planet | accessdate=2013-04-13 | year=2012 | edition=7 | isbn=978-1743213018 }}</ref>\n\n====Asia====\nMacau - Still uses tri-wheels bicycle rickshaw, or Riquex\u00f3 in Portuguese, as Macau was a Portuguese colony in the past, and this kind of transportation were very famous till late 20th century, due to the fact of being a small city and few cars, not so much motorcycle, very bad public transport and none other transport such as train or subway.\nYou can go around Macau peninsula and the two island on rickshaw, and visit the Riquex\u00f3 Museum and see the evolution of rickshaw since 18th till nowadays.\n\nAutomated cycle rickshaws, called velotaxis, are popular in Kyoto and Tokyo, Japan. Their use is growing at a rate of about 20-30% a year in Japanese cities. The traditional rickshaws are still alive for travelers in some tourist places in Japan. Rickshaws are found in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"De Mente p. 95-96\" /> In China, automated and pedal-power cycle rickshaws, or pedicabs, are used for short distance passenger travel in large cities and many medium-sized cities.<ref name=\"Tiki China\" /> Most Indian cities offer [[auto rickshaw]] service; Hand-pulled rickshaws do exist in some areas, such as [[Kolkata]] (Calcutta) as a part of their transport system which also includes cycle rickshaws.<ref>{{cite book | title=Frommer's India | publisher=John Wiley and Sons |author1=Pippa de Bruyn |author2=Keith Bain |author3=David Allardice |author4=Shonar Joshi | location=2010 | pages=15, 57, 156 | isbn=978-0470645802 | edition=Fourth| date=2010-02-18 }}</ref> Sri Lanka has over 1 million auto rickshaws registered in use as of 2018.\n\n====Australia====\nIn Australia, [[Cycle rickshaw]]s or trishaws (3 wheels) are used in [[Melbourne]] and [[St Kilda, Victoria|St Kilda]]. They are also seen in [[Cowaramup, Western Australia]] at Bakehouse '38.\n\n====Europe====\n[[Image:Brighton to Newhaven along the coast 056.jpg|thumb|upright|Auto rickshaw located in [[Brighton Marina]].]]\n[[Cycle rickshaw]]s or trishaws (3 wheels) are used in most large continental European cities,<ref name=IBF /> such as:\n <!-- Australia isn't a part of Europe -->\n* Austria: [[Vienna]]\n* Denmark: [[Copenhagen]] and [[Odense]]<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A4QjqJqi7A8C&pg=PT56 | title=Denmark Travel Adventures | publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc | author=Elizabet Olesen | year=2011 | pages=PT56 | isbn=978-1588437075}}</ref><ref name=MainStreet>{{ cite web | url=http://www.pedicab.com/pedicab-operators.html | title=Main Street Pedicab Operators | publisher=Main Street Pedicabs | accessdate=April 13, 2013 }}</ref>\n* France: [[Paris]] and [[Nantes]]<ref name=MainStreet /> \n* Germany: [[Lake Constance]], [[Berlin]], [[Frankfurt]], [[Hamburg]], [[Hanover]] and other cities.<ref name=IBF>{{ cite web | url=http://www.ibike.org/economics/pedicab-intl.htm | title=Pedicabs, Cycle Rickshaws: International Directory | publisher=International Bicycle Fund | accessdate=April 13, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=MainStreet />\n* Hungary: [[Budapest]]<ref name=MainStreet />\n* Ireland: [[Cork (city)|Cork]] and [[Dublin]].\n* Italy: [[Florence]], [[Milan]],<ref name=MainStreet /> and [[Rome]]\n* The Netherlands: [[Amsterdam]] and in the [[Caribbean]], [[Willemstad]]<ref name=MainStreet /><ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.amsterdam.info/transport/bike-taxi/ | title=Bike taxi | publisher=Amsterdam Tourism & Convention Board | accessdate=April 13, 2013 }}</ref> \n* Norway: [[Oslo]]<ref name=MainStreet />\n* Poland: [[Krak\u00f3w]] and [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]]\n* Russia: [[Saint Petersburg]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greenword.ru/2012/07/velo-riksha.html|title=\u0412\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0448\u0438 \u0432 \u041f\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0435|author=pinokio|work=GreenWord.ru: \u0438\u043b\u043b\u044e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0435\u0442-\u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b \u043e \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\u0435 \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0435|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n* Spain: [[Barcelona]]<ref name=MainStreet />\n* Switzerland: [[Bern]]\n\nWithin the United Kingdom, pedicabs operate in:\n* [[London]], mostly in [[Soho]] and other areas of central London. Their activity is not regulated by [[Transport for London]], so there are no limits of the fees they can charge.<ref name=\"Edgerton p. 46\"/><ref name=MainStreet />{{#tag:ref|Rickshaws or Pedicabs as they are also known, have been operating on the streets of London for over 7 years in and around the West End, Soho, Covent Garden and Leicester Square areas.|group=\"nb\"}}\n* [[Edinburgh]], where vendors are hired like taxis and provide tours.<ref>{{cite book |  title=Frommer's Scotland |author1=Lesley Anne Rose |author2=Michael Macaroon |author3=Vivienne Crow | edition =12 | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | year=2012 | isbn=978-1119992769 }}</ref>\n* [[Oxford]].<ref name=MainStreet />\n\n====America====\n* In Canada there are pedicabs in operation in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]]<ref>{{cite book | title=Vancouver and Victoria. 4th ed. | author=Ulysses Travel Editorial Staff, Ulysses Travel Guides | publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc | year=2003 | isbn=978-2894645178 }}</ref> and [[Vancouver]]. They are regulated in [[Toronto]] and [[Vancouver]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Pedicabs, City of Vancouver | url=http://vancouver.ca/doing-business/pedicabs.aspx | publisher=City of Vancouver | accessdate=April 13, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Rickshaw owners back in driver's seat: Toronto rickshaws can now charge unlimited fares after a judge said City Hall's price limits were chosen on a \"whim.\" | url=http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/toronto/story.html?id=dad7518a-21d5-42d4-8030-d3bae4be6841 | publisher=National Post, CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. (posted on Canada.com) | date=May 9, 2007 | accessdate=April 13, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513005700/http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/toronto/story.html?id=dad7518a-21d5-42d4-8030-d3bae4be6841 | archivedate=May 13, 2013 }}</ref> Pulled rickshaw rides are available in downtown [[Ottawa]], with tours of historical [[Byward Market]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Frommer's Canada: With the best hiking & outdoor adventures |author1=Hilary Davidson |author2=Paul Karr |author3=Herbert Bailey Livesey |author4=Bill McRae |author5=Donald Olson | edition=14 | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | year=2006 | isbn=978-0470044575 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ottawarickshaws.ca/tours-and-services/downtown-rickshaw-tours/ | title=Downtown Ottawa Rickshaw Tours | publisher=Ottawa Rickshaws | accessdate=April 13, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419002430/http://ottawarickshaws.ca/tours-and-services/downtown-rickshaw-tours/ | archivedate=April 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n* In the United States, [[San Diego]] and [[New York City]] each host hundreds of pedicabs; dozens of other North American cities also have [[pedicab]] services.<ref>{{cite book | title=Proceedings of the International Conferences on Transportation Systems Planning and Operation, Volume 1 | author=Indian Institute of Technology (Madras, India). Dept. of Civil Engineering | editor=V. Thamizh Arasan |\npublisher=Allied Publishers | year=2004 | page=202 }}</ref> In New York, human powered transport is used primarily by tourists due to its cost.<ref name=\"concierge NYC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.concierge.com/ideas/hotspots/tours/500723?page=1|title=Travel Inspiration|work=Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"amny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amny.com/urbanite-1.812039/pedicab-driving-no-easy-ride-1.1293582|title=New York City News: Latest Headlines, Videos & Pictures|work=am New York|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|At a rate of $5 plus $1 per block ''per person,'' a 20-block (one mile) pedicab ride for two people will cost $50.<ref name=\"concierge NYC\" /><ref name=amny /> In a taxicab, the same ride would cost under $10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/tlc/html/passenger/taxicab_rate.shtml|title=NYC Taxi & Limousine Commission - RATE OF FARE|publisher=|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref> According to Peter Meitzler of New York's Manhattan Rickshaw Company, a passenger has an entirely different urban experience when one rides in a rickshaw.<ref>[http://www.smithsonianmagazine.com/issues/2007/march/rickshaw.php \"Rickshaws Reinvented - The ancient transportation takes a modern turn\"], Dina Modianot-Fox, Smithsonian Magazine, March 2007</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} In [[New Orleans]], pedicabs have been utilized to transport [[French Quarter]] tourists since the summer of 2012.<ref name=\"Big Breezy Pedaling: The New Orleans Pedicab\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gonola.com/2012/07/06/big-breezy-pedaling-the-new-orleans-pedicab.html|title=Big Breezy Pedaling: The New Orleans Pedicab|work=GoNOLA.com|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n* In Mexico there are thousands of pedicabs. All drivers are  in informal circumstances, and have precarious working conditions, long hours (11.3 hours a day), low wages (US$59.18 per week), and no social protections or benefits. 6.3% reported suffering from a disease, 49.5% corresponded to musculoskeletal conditions and only 11.6% were affiliated to any health system. 53.8% are owners of the vehicle and, although it does not seem to influence physical illness (P=0.03), it is related to the psychosocial ones (P=0.260).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berrones-Sanz|first=Luis David|title=The working conditions of motorcycle taxi drivers in Tl\u00e1huac, Mexico City|journal=Journal of Transport & Health|volume=8|pages=73\u201380|doi=10.1016/j.jth.2017.04.008|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|Rickshaws in the United States}}\n\n==Types==\n{{Commons category|Rickshaws}}\n{{wiktionary}}\nTypes of rickshaws include:\n* a [[pulled rickshaw]]; a two-wheeled passenger cart pulled by a human runner\n* a [[cycle rickshaw]], also called a ''pedicab''\n* an [[auto rickshaw]], also called a ''tuk-tuk, auto,  mototaxi,'' or ''baby taxi''\n* an [[electric rickshaw]], also called ''e-rickshaw''.\n\n<gallery widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\">\nFile:Pousse-pousse_Madagascar.jpg|Pulled rickshaw, [[Madagascar]]\nFile:Riksaw nepal.jpg|Cycle rickshaws, [[Nepal]]\nFile:Auto_Rickshaw_in_San_Francisco.jpg|Auto rickshaw, [[San Francisco, California]]\nFile:Human.rickshaw.kolkata.india.JPG|Pulled Rickshaw in [[Kolkata]]\nFile:Gem_prince.jpg|[[Fibre-reinforced plastic|FRP]],GEM e-rickshaw [[Haryana, India]]\nFile:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Becaks bij de Britse ambassade TMnr 20018038.jpg|[[Cycle rickshaw]] in [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]] known as ''\"Bechak\"''\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-break}}\n;Rickshaws\n* [[Auto rickshaw]]\n* [[Cycle rickshaw]]\n* [[Electric rickshaw]]\n* [[Pulled rickshaw]]\n* [[Rickshaw art]]\n\nDesigner\n* [[George Bliss (pedicab designer)]]\n\n{{col-break}}\n;Other human powered transport\n* [[Bath chair]]\n* [[Human-powered transport]]\n* [[Boda-boda]] (bicycle taxi)\n* [[Bicycle trailer]]\n* [[Freight bicycle]]\n* [[Quadracycle]]\n* [[Utility cycling]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{ cite book | title= Calcutta cycle-rickshaw pullers: a sociological study | author= Bandyopadhyay, Subir | publisher=Minerva Associates Publications | year=1990 | isbn=978-8185195278 }}\n* {{ cite book | title=Reluctant Heroes: Richshaw Pullers in Hong Kong And Canton, 1874-1954 | author = Fung, Chi Ming |agency=Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland | publisher=Hong Kong University Press | year=2005 | isbn=978-9622097346 }}\n* {{ cite book | title=A socio-economic survey of rickshaw drivers in Hyderabad City area | author=Indian Institute of Economics | publisher=A.P. | year=1962 }}\n* {{cite book | title=Solar-assisted Electric Auto Rickshaw Three Wheeler | author = Mulhall, Priscilla | publisher=Illinois Institute of Technology | year= 2010 }}\n* {{cite book | title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 | publisher=NUS Press | author=Warren, James Francis | isbn=978-9971692667 | year=2003 | url=https://archive.org/details/rickshawcooliepe0000warr }}\n\n{{human-powered vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Human-powered vehicles]]\n[[Category:Japanese inventions]]\n[[Category:Rickshaws]]\n[[Category:Vehicles for hire]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Arunuflex", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rickshaw"}
{"title_page": "Adelso Pe\u00f1a", "text_new": "{{short description|Cuban sports shooter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Adelso Pe\u00f1a\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = \n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1953|11|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Shooting sport|Sports shooting]]\n| event          = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Adelso Pe\u00f1a''' (born 10 November 1953) is a Cuban former [[Shooting sport|sports shooter]]. He competed at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1980 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/pe/adelso-pena-1.html |title=Adelso Pe\u00f1a |accessdate=17 February 2016 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pena, Adelso}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cuban male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in shooting]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for Cuba]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for Cuba]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1971 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1979 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1983 Pan American Games]]\n\n\n{{Cuba-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cuban sports shooter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Adelso Pe\u00f1a\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = \n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1953|11|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Shooting sport|Sports shooting]]\n| event          = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Adelso Pe\u00f1a''' (born 10 November 1953) is a Cuban former [[Shooting sport|sports shooter]]. He competed at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1980 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/pe/adelso-pena-1.html |title=Adelso Pe\u00f1a |accessdate=17 February 2016 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pena, Adelso}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cuban male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in shooting]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for Cuba]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for Cuba]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1971 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1979 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1983 Pan American Games]]\n\n\n{{Cuba-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adelso_Pe%C3%B1a"}
{"title_page": "Priyanka Purohit", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian television actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Priyanka Purohit\n| birth_name         = Priyanka Purohit\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1991|10|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai, Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| residence          = [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\n| nationality        = [[India]]n\n| occupation         = [[Actress]]\n| yearsactive        = 2014\u2014present\n| known_for          = ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''<br>''[[Krishnadasi]]''\n}}\n\n'''Priyanka Purohit''' is an Indian television actress known for participating in [[MTV (India)|MTV India]]'s ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]'' and portraying Poorva Deshmukh in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]''.\n\n==Career==\nPurohit started off her career in 2014 by participating in [[MTV India]]'s ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''. In the same year, she made her acting debut as Gauri in [[Sony Pal]]'s ''[[Yeh Dil Sun Raha Hai]].''\n\nIn 2015, she played Pinky in [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Bandhan (Indian TV series)|Bandhan]]'' and Pallavi in [[Life OK]]'s ''[[Kalash - Ek Vishwaas|Kalash]]''. In 2016, Purohit portrayed Poorva Deshmukh in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]'' opposite [[Shravan Reddy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/priyanka-purohit-romance-shravan-krishndasi-160502|title=Priyanka Purohit to romance Shravan in Krishndasi|last=|first=|date=|work=Tellychakkar|access-date=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she joined [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Sanyukt]]'' as Hetal Shah opposite Suraj Kakkar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/priyanka-purohit-and-simran-khanna-zee-tv-s-sanyukt-170104|title=Priyanka Purohit in Zee TV\u2019s Sanyukt|last=|first=|date=|work=Tellychakkar|access-date=|language=en}}</ref> From 2017 to 2018, she portrayed Chandni Kanojia in [[&TV]]'s ''[[Half Marriage (TV series)|Half Marriage]]'' opposite Tarun Mahilani.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/tv/news/hindi/ready-to-witness-a-half-marriage-on-tv/articleshow/60816646.cms|title=Ready to witness a \u2018Half Marriage\u2019 on TV?|last=|first=|date=|work=The Times of India|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2018 to 2019, Purohit portrayed Bhumi in [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]'' .<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iwmbuzz.com/television/news/priyanka-purohit-enter-zee-tvs-aap-ke-aa-jane-se/2018/07/16|title=Priyanka Purohit to enter Zee TV\u2019s Aap Ke Aa Jane Se|work=IWMBuzz|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2019, she played Tara in [[SAB TV]]'s ''Tera Kya Hoga Alia'' opposite [[Harshad Arora]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iwmbuzz.com/television/news/priyanka-purohit-opposite-harshad-arora-optimystix-show-sab-tv/2019/07/08|title=Priyanka Purohit opposite Harshad Arora and Anushka Mishra in Optimystix show on SAB TV|website=IWM Buzz|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Channel\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''\n|Contestant\n|[[MTV India]]\n|-\n|2015\u20132015\n|''[[Yeh Dil Sun Raha Hai]]\n|Gauri\n|[[Sony Pal]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2015\n|''[[Bandhan (Indian TV series)|Bandhan]]\n|Pinky Patil\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|''[[Kalash (2015 TV series)|Kalash]]''\n|Pallavi Deol\n|[[Life OK]]\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]''\n|Poorva Deshmukh\n|[[Colors TV]]\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[Sanyukt]]''\n|Hetal Shah\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|2017\u20132018\n|''[[Half Marriage (TV series)|Half Marriage]]''\n|Chandni Kanojia\n|[[&TV]]\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n|''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]''\n|Bhumi\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|2019\n|''Tera Kya Hoga Alia''\n|Tara\n|[[SAB TV]]\n|}\n\n==Web==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Platform\n|-\n|2020\n|''Sumer Singh Diaries''\n|TBA\n|[[Viu (streaming media)|Viu]]\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Show !! Result !! Reference\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Zee Rishtey Awards]]\n|Favourite Naya Sadasya (Female)\n|''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizasialive.com/zee-rishtey-awards-2018-nominations/|title=Zee Rishtey Awards 2018: Nominations|last=|first=|date=|work=Biz Asia|access-date=|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Purohit, Priyanka}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|8636752}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian television actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Priyanka Purohit\n| birth_name         = Priyanka Purohit\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1991|10|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai, Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| residence          = [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\n| nationality        = [[India]]n\n| occupation         = [[Actress]]\n| yearsactive        = 2014\u2014present\n| known_for          = ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''<br>''[[Krishnadasi]]''\n}}\n\n'''Priyanka Purohit''' is an Indian television actress known for participating in [[MTV (India)|MTV India]]'s ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]'' and portraying Poorva Deshmukh in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]''.\n\n==Career==\nPurohit started off her career in 2014 by participating in [[MTV India]]'s ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''. In the same year, she made her acting debut as Gauri in [[Sony Pal]]'s ''[[Yeh Dil Sun Raha Hai]].''\n\nIn 2015, she played Pinky in [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Bandhan (Indian TV series)|Bandhan]]'' and Pallavi in [[Life OK]]'s ''[[Kalash - Ek Vishwaas|Kalash]]''. In 2016, Purohit portrayed Poorva Deshmukh in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]'' opposite [[Shravan Reddy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/priyanka-purohit-romance-shravan-krishndasi-160502|title=Priyanka Purohit to romance Shravan in Krishndasi|last=|first=|date=|work=Tellychakkar|access-date=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she joined [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Sanyukt]]'' as Hetal Shah opposite Suraj Kakkar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/priyanka-purohit-and-simran-khanna-zee-tv-s-sanyukt-170104|title=Priyanka Purohit in Zee TV\u2019s Sanyukt|last=|first=|date=|work=Tellychakkar|access-date=|language=en}}</ref> From 2017 to 2018, she portrayed Chandni Kanojia in [[&TV]]'s ''[[Half Marriage (TV series)|Half Marriage]]'' opposite Tarun Mahilani.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/tv/news/hindi/ready-to-witness-a-half-marriage-on-tv/articleshow/60816646.cms|title=Ready to witness a \u2018Half Marriage\u2019 on TV?|last=|first=|date=|work=The Times of India|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2018 to 2019, Purohit portrayed Bhumi in [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]'' .<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iwmbuzz.com/television/news/priyanka-purohit-enter-zee-tvs-aap-ke-aa-jane-se/2018/07/16|title=Priyanka Purohit to enter Zee TV\u2019s Aap Ke Aa Jane Se|work=IWMBuzz|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2019, she played Tara in [[SAB TV]]'s ''Tera Kya Hoga Alia'' opposite [[Harshad Arora]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iwmbuzz.com/television/news/priyanka-purohit-opposite-harshad-arora-optimystix-show-sab-tv/2019/07/08|title=Priyanka Purohit opposite Harshad Arora in Optimystix show on SAB TV|website=IWM Buzz|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Channel\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''\n|Contestant\n|[[MTV India]]\n|-\n|2015\u20132015\n|''[[Yeh Dil Sun Raha Hai]]\n|Gauri\n|[[Sony Pal]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2015\n|''[[Bandhan (Indian TV series)|Bandhan]]\n|Pinky Patil\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|''[[Kalash (2015 TV series)|Kalash]]''\n|Pallavi Deol\n|[[Life OK]]\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]''\n|Poorva Deshmukh\n|[[Colors TV]]\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[Sanyukt]]''\n|Hetal Shah\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|2017\u20132018\n|''[[Half Marriage (TV series)|Half Marriage]]''\n|Chandni Kanojia\n|[[&TV]]\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n|''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]''\n|Bhumi\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|2019\n|''Tera Kya Hoga Alia''\n|Tara\n|[[SAB TV]]\n|}\n\n==Web==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Platform\n|-\n|2020\n|''Sumer Singh Diaries''\n|TBA\n|[[Viu (streaming media)|Viu]]\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Show !! Result !! Reference\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Zee Rishtey Awards]]\n|Favourite Naya Sadasya (Female)\n|''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizasialive.com/zee-rishtey-awards-2018-nominations/|title=Zee Rishtey Awards 2018: Nominations|last=|first=|date=|work=Biz Asia|access-date=|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Purohit, Priyanka}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|8636752}}\n", "name_user": "Tylertoney Dude perfect", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCareer:Added a name)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Priyanka_Purohit"}
{"title_page": "Richard Moore (diplomat)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Richard Moore\n| honorific-suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CMG}}\n| office              = Director General, Political, Foreign and Commonwealth Office\n| status              = Incumbent\n| monarch             = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| term_start          = April 2018\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Karen Pierce]]\n| office1             = [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Turkey|British Ambassador to Turkey]]\n| monarch1            = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| term_start1         = January 2014\n| term_end1           = December 2017\n| predecessor1        = [[David Reddaway]]\n| successor1          = [[Dominick Chilcott]]\n| alma_mater          = {{plainlist |\n* [[University of Oxford]] <small>(BA)</small>\n* [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Kennedy School of Government, Harvard University]]\n* [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]]\n| spouse = Margaret Patricia Isabel Martin (Maggie)\n| children = 2\n| birth_place = [[Tripoli]], [[Libya]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|05|09|df=y}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Richard Peter Moore''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CMG|size=100%}} is a British Diplomat who is currently the Director General, Political, at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]].<ref name=\"gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/richard-moore|title=Richard Moore CMG|publisher=[[Government of the United Kingdom|HM Government]]|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-political-director-in-lebanon-discusses-security|title=FCO Political Director in Lebanon, discusses security|publisher=British Embassy Beirut|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ww\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-268831|title=Moore, Richard Peter|publisher=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who 2020]]|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"twitter\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/UKPolDirRichard?s=20|title=Richard Moore @UKPolDirRichard|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> He was also previously the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Turkey|British Ambassador to Turkey]].<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /><ref name=\"twitter\" />\n\n== Education ==\nMoore went to school at the Roman Catholic school, [[St George's College, Weybridge]].<ref name=\"ww\" /> Afterwards, Moore studied [[Philosophy, politics and economics|PPE]] at the [[Worcester College, Oxford]] where he gained a [[Bachelor of Arts|bachelor's degree]].<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /> He then won a [[Kennedy Scholarship]] to study at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Kennedy School of Government]] in [[Harvard University]].<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /> In 2007, he attended the Stanford Executive Programme.<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" />\n\n== Career ==\nRichard's notable career has been in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO)]] and in [[Her Majesty's Diplomatic Service]], the first of which he joined in 1987.<ref name=\"ww\" /> He has had minor postings to [[Vietnam]] 1988, [[Turkey]] (1990, 1991\u20131992), [[Pakistan]] (1995\u201398), [[Iran]] (1992\u201395) and [[Malaysia]] (2001\u20132005).<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /> He was the section head of the Security Policy Group at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|FCO]] from 1998 to 2001 and the Deputy Director of the Middle East from 2005 to 2008.<ref name=\"ww\" />\n\nRichard's first major role in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|FCO]] was Director for Programmes and Change, a post which he held from 2008\u20132010.<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /> He then went on to be Director for Europe, Latin America and Globalisation (2010\u20132012).<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" />\n\nMoore's first public appointment was the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Turkey|British Ambassador to Turkey]]. He held this post for three years, from 2014 to 2017.<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /><ref name=\"twitter\" /> He then took a short stint as Deputy National Security Advisor (Intelligence, Security and Resilience) in 2018.<ref name=\"ww\" /><ref name=\"twitter\" /> His most recent appointment has been Director-General, Political in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|FCO]], a post which he has held since 2018.<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /><ref name=\"twitter\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nMoore was born in [[Tripoli]], [[Libya]] on the 9th of May 1963 to John Robert Moore and (Norah) Patricia Moore (n\u00e9e Buckley)<ref name=\"ww\" /> In 1985, He married Margaret Patricia Isabel Martin (Maggie), who with he has had 1 son and 1 daughter.<ref name=\"ww\" />\n\nIn his spare time, Richard enjoys: [[golf]]; watching [[cricket]] and [[Rugby football|rugby]]; [[reading]]; [[TV]]; [[travel]]; [[hiking]]; [[scuba-diving]]; [[Anatolian rug|Turkish carpets]] and [[Iznik pottery|porcelain]]; and [[Historic site|visiting historical sites]].<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" />\n\n<references />\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Richard Moore\n| honorific-suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CMG}}\n| office              = Director General, Political, Foreign and Commonwealth Office\n| status              = Incumbent\n| monarch             = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| term_start          = April 2018\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Karen Pierce]]\n| office1             = [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Turkey|British Ambassador to Turkey]]\n| monarch1            = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| term_start1         = January 2014\n| term_end1           = December 2017\n| predecessor1        = [[David Reddaway]]\n| successor1          = [[Dominick Chilcott]]\n| alma_mater          = {{plainlist |\n* [[University of Oxford]] <small>(BA)</small>\n* [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Kennedy School of Government, Harvard University]]\n* [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]]\n| spouse = Margaret Patricia Isabel Martin (Maggie)\n| children = 2\n| birth_place = [[Tripoli]], [[Libya]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|05|09|df=y}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Richard Peter Moore''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CMG|size=100%}} is a British Diplomat who is currently the Director General, Political, at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]].<ref name=\"gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/richard-moore|title=Richard Moore CMG|publisher=[[Government of the United Kingdom|HM Government]]|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-political-director-in-lebanon-discusses-security|title=FCO Political Director in Lebanon, discusses security|publisher=British Embassy Beirut|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ww\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-268831|title=Moore, Richard Peter|publisher=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who 2020]]|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"twitter\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/UKPolDirRichard?s=20|title=Richard Moore @UKPolDirRichard|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> He was also previously the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Turkey|British Ambassador to Turkey]].<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /><ref name=\"twitter\" />\n\n== Education ==\nMoore went to school at the Roman Catholic school, [[St George's College, Weybridge]].<ref name=\"ww\" /> Afterwards, Moore studied [[Philosophy, politics and economics|PPE]] at the [[Worcester College, Oxford]] where he gained a [[Bachelor of Arts|bachelor's degree]].<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /> He then won a [[Kennedy Scholarship]] to study at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Kennedy School of Government]] in [[Harvard University]].<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /> In 2007, he attended the Stanford Executive Programme.<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" />\n\n== Career ==\nRichard's notable career has been in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO)]] and in [[Her Majesty's Diplomatic Service]], the first of which he joined in 1987.<ref name=\"ww\" /> He has had minor postings to [[Vietnam]] 1988, [[Turkey]] (1990, 1991\u20131992), [[Pakistan]] (1995\u201398), [[Iran]] (1992\u201395) and [[Malaysia]] (2001\u20132005).<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /> He was the section head of the Security Policy Group at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|FCO]] from 1998 to 2001 and the Deputy Director of the Middle East from 2005 to 2008.<ref name=\"ww\" />\n\nRichard's first major role in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|FCO]] was Director for Programmes and Change, a post which he held from 2008\u20132010.<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /> He then went on to be Director for Europe, Latin America and Globalisation (2010\u20132012).<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" />\n\nMoore's first public appointment was the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Turkey|British Ambassador to Turkey]]. He held this post for three years, from 2014 to 2017.<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /><ref name=\"twitter\" /> He then took a short stint as Deputy National Security Advisor (Intelligence, Security and Resilience) in 2018.<ref name=\"ww\" /><ref name=\"twitter\" /> His most recent appointment has been Director-General, Political in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|FCO]], a post which he has held since 2018.<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" /><ref name=\"twitter\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nMoore was born in [[Tripoli]], [[Libya]] on the 9th of May 1963 to John Robert Moore and (Norah) Patricia Moore (n\u00e9e Buckley)<ref name=\"ww\" /> In 1985, He married Margaret Patricia Isabel Martin (Maggie), who with he has had 1 son and 1 daughter.<ref name=\"ww\" />\n\nIn his spare time, Richard enjoys: [[golf]]; watching [[cricket]] and [[rugby]]; [[reading]]; [[TV]]; [[travel]]; [[hiking]]; [[scuba-diving]]; [[Anatolian rug|Turkish carpets]] and [[Iznik pottery|porcelain]]; and [[Historic site|visiting historical sites]].<ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"ww\" />\n\n<references />\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Godtres", "label": "safe", "comment": "Further Hyperlink Edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Moore_(diplomat)"}
{"title_page": "Rathore", "text_new": "{{for|the village|Rathor, Pakistan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n\n\nThe '''Rathore''' is a clan of [[Rajputs]] found in Northern India.<ref>{{cite book |author=A. M. Shah |title=The Family in India: Critical Essays |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U8s0aBdDxEQC&pg=PA112 |year=1998 |publisher=Orient Blackswan |isbn=978-81-250-1306-8 |page=112}}</ref> The Rathore deduce their origin from the Rath (Spine) of [[Indra]]. Several sources state the origin of the Rathore's from the [[Rashtrakuta dynasty]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=6dR0CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&dq=rashtrakuta+rathore&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiw2vr5qcznAhVSb30KHVX7AasQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q&f=false Royal Umbrellas of Stone: Memory, Politics, and Public Identity in Rajput funerary art By Melia Belli Bose pg.140]</ref> Some bards of [[Rajputana]] and  [[Prithviraj Raso]], also called the Rathore's descendants of the [[Gahadvala]]s, however the [[Gahadvala]] claims were of later origin, and their historical veracity is doubtful.<ref>[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=EJQBAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y The History of the G\u0101ha\u1e0dav\u0101la Dynasty by Roma Niyogi pg.29-31]</ref> The Rathore rulers referred to themselves as the successors of the [[Rashtrakuta dynasty]] and tried to get an imperial status by this claim when they were at the height of their power in the 16th century.<ref>Medieval India (1526\u20131748) Part two. by Satish Chandra. p. 79</ref> The Rathore clan stood high amongst the 36 Royal Rajput tribes and the Rathore cavalry was formerly known as the best in India.<ref>[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=mc6C5dVHbGAC&dq=The+Indian+Encyclopaedia:+Mahi-Mewat+by+Subodh+Kapoor&source=gbs_navlinks_s The Indian Encyclopaedia: Mahi-Mewat by Subodh Kapoor pg.4708]</ref> \n\nSome of the [[Maratha]] clans claim to be of Rathore origin. However they claim descent from the [[Lunar dynasty|Somavansha]],<ref name=\"ATCarter\">{{cite journal |author=Anthony T. Carter |title=Caste 'boundaries' and the principle of kinship amity: a Maratha caste Purana |journal=Contributions to Indian Sociology |volume=9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iLVLAQAAIAAJ |year=1975 |publisher=Mouton |page=130 |quote=The Somavansha, for example, consists of nine gotras: Chavan, More, Pawar, Ganganaik, Rathod, Dhampal, Jagtap, Chaluke, and Kachre. }}</ref> unlike the [[Rajput]] Rathore's who claim descent from the [[Suryavansha]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Indian India|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WfU8AQAAIAAJ|publisher = Director of Public Relations, Chamber of Princes|date = 1 January 1945|language = en}}</ref> in gujarat Rathod clan also found in [[Kolis]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shah|first=A. M.|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=U8s0aBdDxEQC&pg=PA127&dq=Talpada+Kolis+Rathod&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQtozFhuroAhXRUn0KHf2OBxoQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=Talpada%20Kolis%20Rathod&f=false|title=The Family in India: Critical Essays|date=1998|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-81-250-1306-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Williams|first=Raymond Brady|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=rs5JDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT354&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Swaminarayan Hinduism: Tradition, Adaptation, and Identity|last2=Trivedi|first2=Yogi|date=2016-05-12|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-908959-8|language=en}}</ref> \n\nAlternative spellings include '''Rathaur''' or '''Rathor''' or '''Rathur''' or '''Rathod''' or '''Rathour''' or '''Rahtore'''.\n\n==Rathore states==\nThe various cadet branches of the Rathore clan gradually spread to encompass all of Marwar and later founded states in Central India and Gujarat. At the time of India's independence in 1947, \"these nine Rathore States collectively brought to India territory not less than 60,000 square miles in area\". The princely states ruled by various branches of the Rathore clan included:<ref>{{cite book |title=The House of Marwar|author=Dhananajaya Singh|publisher=Lotus Collection, Roli Books|year=1994|page=13|quote=The Rathore clan of Rajputs, a clan which besides Jodhpur had ruled over Bikaner, Kishengarh, Idar, Jhabhua, Sitamau, Sailana, Alirajpur and Ratlam, all States important enough to merit gun salutes in the British system of protocol. These nine Rathore States collectively brought to India territory not less than 60,000 square miles in area.}}</ref>\n\n*[[Jodhpur State|Jodhpur]] (Marwar) in present-day Rajasthan, founded in 1226 by Rao Sheoji.\n*[[Bikaner State|Bikaner]] in present-day Rajasthan, founded in 1465 by Rao Bika.\n*[[Kishangarh State|Kishangarh]] in present-day Rajasthan, founded in 1611 by Raja Kishan Singh.\n*[[Idar State|Idar]] in present-day Gujarat, founded in 1729 by Rao Anand Singh.\n*[[Ratlam State|Ratlam]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded in 1651 by Maharaja Ratan Singh.\n*[[Jhabua State|Jhabua]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded in 1584 by Raja Keshav Das.\n*[[Sitamau State|Sitamau]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded 1701 by Raja Kesho Das.\n*[[Sailana State|Sailana]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded in 1730 by Raja Jai Singh.\n*[[Alirajpur State|Alirajpur]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded in 1437 by Raja Anand Deo.\n\n==Notable people==\n\nSee \n* [[Rathore (surname)]]\n* [[Rathod (surname)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Rajput Groups of India}}\n\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the village|Rathor, Pakistan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n\n\nThe '''Rathore''' is a clan of [[Rajputs]] found in Northern India.<ref>{{cite book |author=A. M. Shah |title=The Family in India: Critical Essays |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U8s0aBdDxEQC&pg=PA112 |year=1998 |publisher=Orient Blackswan |isbn=978-81-250-1306-8 |page=112}}</ref> The Rathore deduce their origin from the Rath (Spine) of [[Indra]]. Several sources state the origin of the Rathore's from the [[Rashtrakuta dynasty]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=6dR0CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&dq=rashtrakuta+rathore&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiw2vr5qcznAhVSb30KHVX7AasQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q&f=false Royal Umbrellas of Stone: Memory, Politics, and Public Identity in Rajput funerary art By Melia Belli Bose pg.140]</ref> Some bards of [[Rajputana]] and  [[Prithviraj Raso]], also called the Rathore's descendants of the [[Gahadvala]]s, however the [[Gahadvala]] claims were of later origin, and their historical veracity is doubtful.<ref>[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=EJQBAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y The History of the G\u0101ha\u1e0dav\u0101la Dynasty by Roma Niyogi pg.29-31]</ref> The Rathore rulers referred to themselves as the successors of the [[Rashtrakuta dynasty]] and tried to get an imperial status by this claim when they were at the height of their power in the 16th century.<ref>Medieval India (1526\u20131748) Part two. by Satish Chandra. p. 79</ref> The Rathore clan stood high amongst the 36 Royal Rajput tribes and the Rathore cavalry was formerly known as the best in India.<ref>[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=mc6C5dVHbGAC&dq=The+Indian+Encyclopaedia:+Mahi-Mewat+by+Subodh+Kapoor&source=gbs_navlinks_s The Indian Encyclopaedia: Mahi-Mewat by Subodh Kapoor pg.4708]</ref> \n\nSome of the [[Maratha]] clans claim to be of Rathore origin. However they claim descent from the [[Lunar dynasty|Somavansha]],<ref name=\"ATCarter\">{{cite journal |author=Anthony T. Carter |title=Caste 'boundaries' and the principle of kinship amity: a Maratha caste Purana |journal=Contributions to Indian Sociology |volume=9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iLVLAQAAIAAJ |year=1975 |publisher=Mouton |page=130 |quote=The Somavansha, for example, consists of nine gotras: Chavan, More, Pawar, Ganganaik, Rathod, Dhampal, Jagtap, Chaluke, and Kachre. }}</ref> unlike the [[Rajput]] Rathore's who claim descent from the [[Suryavansha]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Indian India|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WfU8AQAAIAAJ|publisher = Director of Public Relations, Chamber of Princes|date = 1 January 1945|language = en}}</ref> \n\nAlternative spellings include '''Rathaur''' or '''Rathor''' or '''Rathur''' or '''Rathod''' or '''Rathour''' or '''Rahtore'''.\n\n==Rathore states==\nThe various cadet branches of the Rathore clan gradually spread to encompass all of Marwar and later founded states in Central India and Gujarat. At the time of India's independence in 1947, \"these nine Rathore States collectively brought to India territory not less than 60,000 square miles in area\". The princely states ruled by various branches of the Rathore clan included:<ref>{{cite book |title=The House of Marwar|author=Dhananajaya Singh|publisher=Lotus Collection, Roli Books|year=1994|page=13|quote=The Rathore clan of Rajputs, a clan which besides Jodhpur had ruled over Bikaner, Kishengarh, Idar, Jhabhua, Sitamau, Sailana, Alirajpur and Ratlam, all States important enough to merit gun salutes in the British system of protocol. These nine Rathore States collectively brought to India territory not less than 60,000 square miles in area.}}</ref>\n\n*[[Jodhpur State|Jodhpur]] (Marwar) in present-day Rajasthan, founded in 1226 by Rao Sheoji.\n*[[Bikaner State|Bikaner]] in present-day Rajasthan, founded in 1465 by Rao Bika.\n*[[Kishangarh State|Kishangarh]] in present-day Rajasthan, founded in 1611 by Raja Kishan Singh.\n*[[Idar State|Idar]] in present-day Gujarat, founded in 1729 by Rao Anand Singh.\n*[[Ratlam State|Ratlam]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded in 1651 by Maharaja Ratan Singh.\n*[[Jhabua State|Jhabua]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded in 1584 by Raja Keshav Das.\n*[[Sitamau State|Sitamau]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded 1701 by Raja Kesho Das.\n*[[Sailana State|Sailana]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded in 1730 by Raja Jai Singh.\n*[[Alirajpur State|Alirajpur]] in present-day Madhya Pradesh, founded in 1437 by Raja Anand Deo.\n\n==Notable people==\n\nSee \n* [[Rathore (surname)]]\n* [[Rathod (surname)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Rajput Groups of India}}\n\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "PawanjiGupta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added information with references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rathore"}
{"title_page": "Park Chu-young", "text_new": "{{about|a footballer|the long-distance runner|Park Ju-young}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Korean name|Park}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Park Chu-young\n| image              = FC\uc11c\uc6b8 2016 K\ub9ac\uadf8 \uc6b0\uc2b9! \ud669\uc120\ud64d\uac10\ub3c5 \ubc15\uc8fc\uc601, \ub2e4\uce74\ud558\uae30 \uc778\ud130\ubdf0 0.51 minutes Scene.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Park Chu-young in November 2016\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1985|7|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Daegu]], South Korea\n| height             = 1.82 m<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/players/profile.html/chu-young-park|title=Player Profile: Chu-Young Park|publisher=Premier League|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref>\n| position           = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub        = [[FC Seoul]]\n| clubnumber         = 10\n| youthyears1        = 2001\u20132003 |youthclubs1 = [[Cheonggu High School]]\n| youthyears2        = 2002      |youthclubs2 = \u2192 [[Zico Football Center]] (loan)\n| youthyears3        = 2004      |youthclubs3 = [[Korea University]]\n| years1             = 2005\u20132008 |clubs1 = [[FC Seoul]]                            |caps1 = 69 |goals1 = 23\n| years2             = 2008\u20132011 |clubs2 = [[AS Monaco|Monaco]]                    |caps2 = 91 |goals2 = 25\n| years3             = 2011\u20132014 |clubs3 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]                |caps3 = 1  |goals3 = 0\n| years4             = 2012\u20132013 |clubs4 = \u2192 [[Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]] (loan)  |caps4 = 22 |goals4 = 3\n| years5             = 2014      |clubs5 = \u2192 [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] (loan)      |caps5 = 2  |goals5 = 0\n| years6             = 2014\u20132015     |clubs6 = [[Al Shabab FC (Riyadh)|Al-Shabab]] |caps6 = 7  |goals6 = 1\n| years7             = 2015\u2013         |clubs7 = [[FC Seoul]]                        |caps7 = 146 |goals7 = 38\n| nationalyears1 = 2003\u20132005 |nationalteam1 = [[South Korea national under-20 football team|South Korea U20]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 26 | nationalgoals1 = 18\n| nationalyears2 = 2006\u20132012 |nationalteam2 = [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korea U23]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 30 | nationalgoals2 = 12\n| nationalyears4 = 2005\u20132014 |nationalteam4 = [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 68 | nationalgoals4 = 24\n| pcupdate           = 1 December 2019\n| ntupdate           =\n| medaltemplates     = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{KOR}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]]|[[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EAFF East Asian Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2008 East Asian Football Championship|2008 China]]|[[2008 East Asian Football Championship Final squads#South Korea|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2010 Asian Games|2010 Guangzhou]]|[[Football at the 2010 Asian Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[AFC Youth Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2004 AFC Youth Championship|2004 Malaysia]]|}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul = {{lang|ko|{{linktext|\ubc15|\uc8fc|\uc601}}}}\n|hanja = {{lang|ko|{{linktext|\u6734|\u4e3b|\u6c38}}}}\n|rr = Bak Ju-yeong\n|mr = Pak Chu-y\u014fng\n}}\n\n'''Park Chu-young''' ({{korean|hangul=\ubc15\uc8fc\uc601|hanja=\u6734\u4e3b\u6c38}}; {{IPA-ko|pak\u031a.t\u0348\u0255u.j\u028c\u014b}}; also [[Korean romanization|romanised]] as '''Park Ju-young'''; born 10 July 1985) is a South Korean [[association football|footballer]]has been described by many as being a leg-end of the English game, most noted for his spells at Arsenal and Watford where his combined tally of 3 games and 0 goals put him on par with other legends of the English game - Thierry Henry, Ruud van Nistelrooy, Alan Shearer, Fernando Torres, Wayne Rooney to name but a few. who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[FC\n\n==Club career==\n===Youth career===\nPark Chu-young participated at the [[2004 AFC Youth Championship]], where he led the South Korean [[South Korea national under-20 football team|under-20 national team]] to a record-breaking eleventh title. In the process, he won the Golden Ball Award and was chosen Most Valuable Player of the tournament.{{cn|date=August 2019}} Park also participated at the [[2005 FIFA World Youth Championship]], where he scored a goal from a free kick against [[Nigeria national under-20 football team|Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sports.news.naver.com/general/news/read.nhn?oid=079&aid=0000041791|title='\ubc15\uc8fc\uc601 \uc2e0\ub4dc\ub86c \uacc4\uc18d\ub41c\ub2e4' \uae30\uc801\uc758 \uc5ed\uc804\uc2b9(Park Joo-young's come-from-behind victory of the miracle.)|last=Ji Eun|first=Park|date=2005-06-16|work=nocutnews|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===FC Seoul===\n[[File:ParkChuYoung070408.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Park Chu-young playing for FC Seoul in 2007.]]\n\nIn February 2005, Park joined the [[K League Classic|K League]], where he signed with [[FC Seoul]] with highest salary as rookie player<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LPOD&mid=tvh&oid=055&aid=0000039588|title=\ubc15\uc8fc\uc601, K\ub9ac\uadf8 \ub6f4\ub2e4|language=Korean |publisher=[[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS News]]|date=28 February 2005}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://m.fcseoul.com/mobile/news_tv/fcnews_view.jsp?seq=29&tcd=news&pg=271|title=\ubc15\uc8fc\uc601 FC\uc11c\uc6b8 \uc804\uaca9 \uc785\ub2e8|language=Korean |publisher=FC Seoul.com|date=1 March 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn Park's first season, he scored in second appearance.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LPOD&mid=tvh&oid=052&aid=0000070239|script-title=ko:\ubc15\uc8fc\uc601, \ub450 \uacbd\uae30 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \ub370\ubdd4\uace8 \ud3ed\ubc1c|language=Korean |publisher=[[YTN|YTN News]]|date=13 March 2005}}</ref> Eventually, he scored 18 goals and gave 4 assists in 30 appearances (including [[Korean League Cup|League Cup]] matches), earning him the [[K League Rookie of the Year]] award by common consent and its first time in [[K League]] history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LPOD&mid=tvh&oid=052&aid=0000101788|title=\ubc15\uc8fc\uc601, '\ub9cc\uc7a5\uc77c\uce58' K\ub9ac\uadf8 \uc2e0\uc778\uc655|language=Korean |publisher=[[YTN|YTN News]]|date=12 December 2005}}</ref> and becoming top scorer of the competition. He became FC Seoul's club icon.\n\nJust as the [[2007 K League]] kicked off, Park began the season by scoring 10 goals in 11 matches (including Cup games). But soon he was hampered by an on and off foot injury that he sustained during the regular season. Due to the injury he was placed in the reserves for the South Korea national team for the [[2007 AFC Asian Cup]], but he did not recover from injury in time, nor were any of the forwards picked for the South Korea national football team injured or underperformed at the training camp or friendly matches, which resulted in a cut from the South Korea national football team for the [[2007 AFC Asian Cup]]. Also during the time of his injury he was forced to miss the [[FC Seoul]] unfriendly with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].\n\nReturning from his foot injury, he played in the qualification rounds for the [[2008 Olympic Games]], in which South Korea secured a place by drawing 0\u20130 with Bahrain on 27 November 2007.\n\n===AS Monaco===\nAfter impressive performances in the national and Olympic team squads, Park completed a move to [[AS Monaco FC|AS Monaco]] on 1 September 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monaco hire Park|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11800/4083159/monaco-hire-park|publisher=Sky Sports|date=1 September 2008|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> On 13 September, he scored on his debut against [[FC Lorient]] in the 26th minute. In the 2nd half, he assisted his teammate [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Nimani]]'s goal before being substituted. The game ended 2\u20130, and Park was named as the Man of the Match.<ref>{{cite news|title=MATCH STATS: AS MONACO 2 - 0 FC LORIENT|url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/52296|publisher=Ligue 1|language=French|date=13 September 2008|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref>  In his first season at Monaco, he went on to make 31 appearance, scoring five times.\n\nIn his second season at Monaco, Park scored three goals in the first half of the season. On 30 January 2010, Park signed a three-year contract with Monaco that would keep him until 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chu-Young extends Monaco deal|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11800/5899594/chu-young-extends-monaco-deal|publisher=Sky Sports|date=30 January 2010|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> Despite having three injuries during the season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Foot - L1 - Monaco : Park et Muratori bless\u00e9s|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Park-et-muratori-blesses/52782|publisher=L'Equipe|language=French|date=15 August 2009|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sans Park contre l'OM|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Sans-park-contre-l-om/89114|publisher=L'Equipe|language=French|date=11 February 2010|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Foot - L1 - Monaco : Saison termin\u00e9e pour Park|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Saison-terminee-pour-park/105848|publisher=L'Equipe|language=French|date=6 May 2010|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> Park remained on the first team, as he scored eight goals in twenty-seven appearance.\n\nHis last season at Monaco gave him mixed results. Park scored five goals in the first half of the season. But then, after scoring against [[FC Sochaux-Montb\u00e9liard|Sochaux]], Park celebrated, which resulted him injuring his right knee and kept him out for four weeks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Park out for four weeks|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11800/6616842/park-out-for-four-weeks|publisher=Sky Sports|date=26 December 2010|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> On 13 February 2011, Park scored his seventh goal of the season in a 3\u20131 win over [[FC Lorient]]. Thirteen days later, Park scored a brace in a 2\u20132 home draw over [[SM Caen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ligue1.com/ligue1/feuille_match/53900 |title=Match Stats AS Monaco FC \u2013 SM Caen |publisher=Ligue 1 |date=26 February 2011}}</ref> He made a good display in the 2010\u201311 season, scoring twelve league goals, the club, however, was relegated to Ligue 2 after finishing 18th place in the league.\n\nThe relegation led Park to announce his desire to leave Monaco to play in a competitive league.<ref>{{cite news|title=Park seeks Monaco exit|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11672/6963819/park-seeks-monaco-exit|publisher=Sky Sports|date=2 June 2011|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> This was followed up by the club, who stated they wouldn't stand in Park's way from leaving the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Park free to leave Monaco|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11661/7004996/park-free-to-leave-monaco|publisher=Sky Sports|date=2 June 2011|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Arsenal===\n[[File:Park Chu-Young Arsenal.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Park Chu-young at Arsenal]]\nIn somewhat strange circumstances on 30 August 2011, English [[Premier League]] club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] signed Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/950986/arsenal-seal-deal-for-striker-park-chu-young?cc=5739|title=Arsenal seal Park Chu-Young deal|date=30 August 2011|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref> It is believed Chu-Young became aware of Arsenal's interest and departed his hotel room without finishing a medical with the Ligue 1 club [[Lille OSC]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/8727273/Arsenal-steal-South-Korean-idol-Park-Chu-Young-from-Lille.html \"Arsenal steal South Korean idol Park Chu-Young from Lille\"] The Telegraph 27 August 2011 Retrieved 2 September 2012</ref> He was given the number 9 shirt.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/arsenal-to-sign-striker-chu-young-park |title=Arsenal to sign striker Ju Young Park |publisher=Arsenal F.C |date=30 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928013437/http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/arsenal-to-sign-striker-chu-young-park |archivedate=28 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 1 November, Chu-young started his first [[UEFA Champions League]] match, a 0\u20130 draw against French outfit [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]. He scored his first goal for Arsenal in the fourth round of the [[Football League Cup]] against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on 25 October 2011 giving them a 2\u20131 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=332764&cc=5739\n|title=Gunners saved by quickfire double|date=25 October 2011|work=ESPN|accessdate=23 August 2012 }}</ref> He made his league debut for Arsenal as a substitute, 82 minutes into a 2\u20131 home defeat by [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], on 22 January 2012.\n\nOn 6 March 2012, he made an appearance as a substitute for [[Theo Walcott]] in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], in the 3\u20130 win against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] at the [[Emirates Stadium]], though Milan won 4\u20133 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|first=Chris|last=Bevan|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/17187875|title=Arsenal 3 - 0 AC Milan (agg 3 - 4)|work=BBC Sport|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2012, it was confirmed that the forward had been reassigned the number 30 shirt, with new signing [[Lukas Podolski]] taking over the number 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/squad-numbers-updated-for-start-of-season|title=Squad numbers updated for start of season|work=Arsenal Football Club|accessdate=22 August 2012|date=17 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820042120/http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/squad-numbers-updated-for-start-of-season|archivedate=20 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following a loan spell at Celta Vigo, Park was advised by newly national coach [[Hong Myung-bo]] to leave the club if Park was to remain in the national team.<ref>{{cite news|title=South Korea coach warns striker Park Chu-Young to leave Arsenal|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/17247/8917003/south-korea-coach-warns-striker-park-chu-young-to-leave-arsenal|publisher=Sky Sports|date=11 September 2013|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nPark did not play a game for Arsenal for another 14 months until 30 October 2013 when he came on as a substitute for Aaron Ramsey on the 81st minute against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the League Cup. Arsenal lost the game 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24619361|title=Arsenal 0\u20132 Chelsea|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 October 2013|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> Although there was a discussion of a possible loan move to [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]], the deal never materialized.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/10/16/wigan-confirm-plans-to-sign-arsenal-flop-park-chu-young-on-loan-4148642/|title=Wigan confirm plans to sign Arsenal flop Park Chu-Young on-loan|publisher=Metro |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/arsenal-misfit-park-chu-young-being-2347490|title=Arsenal misfit Park Chu-Young being lined up for loan move to Wigan|publisher=Mirror|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom that point forward, Park did not make any further appearances in the league with the first team. Park was released by the club on a free transfer on 30 June 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Clubs submit retained and released lists |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/2013-14/may/premier-league-clubs-submit-retained-and-released-lists.html |accessdate=23 May 2014 |work=[[Premier League]] |date=23 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504185633/http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/2013-14/may/premier-league-clubs-submit-retained-and-released-lists.html |archivedate= 4 May 2015 }}</ref> As a result of his flop at Arsenal, [[Daily Telegraph]] reporter John Duerden would compare Park move to Arsenal as ''\"the worst call to answer since Colin Farrell picked up a New York public phone in Phone Booth and endured a few hours of misery.\"''<ref>{{cite news|title=South Korea striker Park Chu-Young damaged by Arsenal experience thanks to Arsene Wenger|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/south-korea/10655438/South-Korea-striker-Park-Chu-Young-damaged-by-Arsenal-experience-thanks-to-Arsene-Wenger.html|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=22 February 2014|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Loan spells====\nAmidst reported interest from [[Blackburn Rovers]] and [[Al-Hilal FC|Al Hilal]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2012/08/10/arsenal-tell-flop-striker-park-chu-young-he-must-find-new-club-530371/ |title=Arsenal tell flop striker Park Chu-Young he must find new club |publisher=Metro |accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref> and rumours of being linked to [[Nottingham Forest]], on 31 August 2012, Park moved to [[Celta de Vigo]] on a season-long loan from [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]] for the [[2012\u201313 La Liga]] season. He was given the number 18 shirt.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ko:\u2018\uc140\ud0c0 \ube44\uace0\u2019 \uc774\uc801 \ubc15\uc8fc\uc601, \ub4f1\ubc88\ud638 18\ubc88 \ud655\uc815|url=http://sports.news.naver.com/sports/index.nhn?category=worldfootball&ctg=news&mod=read&office_id=410&article_id=0000019380|language=Korean|newspaper=MK Sports|date=1 September 2012}}</ref>  On 22 September 2012, he scored his first goal in his home debut in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Getafe CF|Getafe]], becoming the first South Korean player ever to score a goal in [[La Liga]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u00a1Bienvenidos al Celta Park!|url=http://www.marca.com/2012/09/22/futbol/1adivision/1348336810.html|publisher=MARCA.COM|accessdate=22 September 2012}}</ref> Park would then score two more goals against [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Celta, Mallorca share the points|url=http://www.football-espana.net/26120/celta-mallorca-share-points|publisher=Football Espana|date=18 November 2012|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> and [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo]] in the [[Galician derby]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Liga - Deportivo-Celta de Vigo: Ox\u00edgeno para Riazor (3-1)|url=https://es.eurosport.yahoo.com/noticias/liga-deportivo-celta-de-vigo-ox%C3%ADgeno-riazor-3-224006448.html|publisher=Yahoo! Eurosport|language=Spanish|date=15 March 2013|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> Park would injure his right foot, which put him the end to this season and went on to score three goals in twenty one appearance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Javi Varas sufre un esguince en su mu\u00f1eca derecha|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/04/23/futbol/equipos/celta/1366726364.html|publisher=Marca.com|language=Spanish|date=23 April 2013|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2014, Park was loaned to [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] for the remainder of the 2013\u201314 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140131-park-signs-1332274.aspx |title=Park Arrives On Loan |publisher=Watford F.C. |date=31 January 2014 |accessdate=31 January 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202204032/http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140131-park-signs-1332274.aspx |archivedate=2 February 2014 |url-status=unfit }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/ju-young-park-joins-watford-on-loan |title= Ju Young Park joins Watford on loan |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=31 January 2014 |accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref> Park made his Watford debut as a 90th-minute substitute for [[Fernando Forestieri]] in the 2\u20130 win against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton]] on 2 February 2014<ref>{{cite news|title=Watford 2 - 0 Brighton & Hove Albion|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25900486|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2014|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> and then made his first start for Watford in a 2\u20130 away loss against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on 22 February 2014 before he came off in the second half.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolton Wanderers 2 - 0 Watford|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26201968|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 February 2014|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> However, Park only made two appearance for the club after sustaining injuries to his thigh and toe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140311-sannino-watford-v-doncaster-preview-1411700.aspx |title=PREVIEW: \"Moment To Mark The Situation\" |publisher=Watford F.C. |accessdate=20 December 2014 |date=11 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220150811/http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140311-sannino-watford-v-doncaster-preview-1411700.aspx |archivedate=20 December 2014 |url-status=unfit }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140403-injury-update-1465629.aspx |title=INJURIES: Treatment Room News |publisher=Watford F.C. |accessdate=20 December 2014 |date=3 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220150815/http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/140403-injury-update-1465629.aspx |archivedate=20 December 2014 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Park Chu-Young Celta 2012.JPG|thumb|150px|right|Park Chu-young playing for Celta Vigo.]]\n\n===Al-Shabab===\nDespite his intention to stay in Europe after being released by Arsenal,<ref>{{cite news|title=Out of favor with Arsenal, Park Chu-young seeks to stay in Europe: agent|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2014/07/01/0200000000AEN20140701001400315.html|work=[[Yonhap|Yonhap News Agency]]|date=1 July 2014|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> Park joined Saudi Arabian side [[Al Shabab FC (Riyadh)|Al-Shabab]] on 1 October 2014, signing a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=South Korean striker Park joins Saudi side Al-Shabab|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/sports/2014/10/01/South-Korean-striker-Park-joins-Saudi-side-Al-Shabab.html|publisher=Al Arabiya News|date=1 October 2014|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> Park scored on his debut, in a 1\u20130 victory against [[Al-Hilal FC|Al-Hilal]] on 17 October 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fifa match report website|url=https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/nationalleagues/nationalleague=saudi-arabia-saudi-professional-league-2000000091/matches/match=al-hilal-al-shabab-300294853/index.html|publisher=FIFA|date=17 October 2014|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Return to FC Seoul===\nPark returned to [[FC Seoul]] on 10 March 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fcseoul.com/news/news_view.jsp?news_seq=2&news_type=NEWS_LIST&part=News&seq=3289 |script-title=ko:\ubc15\uc8fc\uc601 \uce5c\uc815\ud300 FC\uc11c\uc6b8\uc5d0\uc11c \u2018\ucd95\uad6c\ucc9c\uc7ac\u2019 \uba85\uc131 \ub418\ucc3e\ub294\ub2e4 |publisher=FC Seoul |date=2015-03-10|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/2340671/former-arsenal-striker-park-chu-young-returning-to-south-korea |title=Former Arsenal striker Park Chu-Young returning to South Korea |publisher=[[ESPN]]FC.com |date=10 March 2015|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> On 6 November 2016, he scored the only goal for FC Seoul in a 1\u20130 away victory against [[Jeonbuk Hyundai Motors]] in the final round of the season, helping his team to win the [[2016 K League Classic|2016]] league title.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2016/11/05/0200000000AEN20161105002200315.html|title=Ex-Arsenal man Park Chu-young leads S. Korean football club to champions|author=Joo Kyung-don|date=7 November 2016|accessdate=29 November 2016|publisher=english.yonhapnews.co.kr}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n\n===2010 FIFA World Cup===\nOn 17 June 2010, Park scored an own goal in a 4\u20131 defeat to [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_18/default.stm|title=Argentina 4\u20131 South Korea|date=17 June 2010|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Jonathan|last=Stevenson|accessdate=2010-06-17}}</ref> However, Park redeemed himself in Korea's next match against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] by scoring a crucial free kick in a 2\u20132 draw, allowing the South Korea to advance to the round of 16. In the round of 16, Park's free kick just before halftime struck the left goal post. A late goal from [[Luis Su\u00e1rez]] put [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] on top. The final score was 2\u20131 to Uruguay who then advanced to the quarter-finals in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] at the expense of South Korea.\n\n===2010 Asian Games===\nPark, along with [[Kim Jung-woo]], was called to the [[South Korea national under-23 football team|U-23 team]] to participate in the [[2010 Asian Games]] held in [[Guangzhou]]. The team was led by former national team captain [[Hong Myung-bo]]. Park did not play in the first game against [[North Korea national under-23 football team|North Korea]], which ended in a 0\u20131 loss. He came off the bench in the next game against [[Jordan national under-23 football team|Jordan]], which South Korea won 4\u20130. He started the last group game against [[Palestine national under-23 football team|Palestine]], in which he scored the second goal in the 3\u20130 victory before being substituted. South Korea advanced to the knockout round, having finished second place in Group C with six points. In their next match against [[China national under-23 football team|China]], Park played the entire game, scoring a goal in the 50th minute to help South Korea to a 3\u20130 win. In the quarterfinal match against [[Uzbekistan national under-23 football team|Uzbekistan]], Park was once again influential in leading Korea to victory. Park scored his third goal of the tournament a few minutes into the first period of extra time, after the teams played to a 1\u20131 draw in normal time. South Korea eventually won the game 3\u20131, and Park was substituted in the 108th minute. Although Park played in the semifinal match against [[United Arab Emirates national football team|UAE]], he was unable to find the net and South Korea lost 0\u20131 after UAE scored in the last minute of extra time. In the bronze medal game against [[Iran national under-23 football team|Iran]], Park scored his fourth goal of the tournament. With South Korea trailing 3\u20131, Park tapped in the ball from a cross to bring the score to 3\u20132. South Korea eventually won 4\u20133 to secure the bronze medal, with two goals from [[Ji Dong-won]].\n\n===2011 AFC Asian Cup===\nAlthough Park had been listed on the roster for the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup]], he was unable to participate due to an injury and was replaced on the roster by [[Ji Dong-won]]. Following the tournament, he was named captain of the national team to replace the retiring [[Park Ji-sung]]. But in 2012, newly appointed head coach [[Choi Kang-hee (footballer)|Choi Kang-hee]] named [[Lee Jung-soo]] as captain of the national side, replacing Park Chu-young.\n\n===2012 London Olympics===\nIn October 2011, Park announced that in two years time he had to leave [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] to do military service for his country, which may have delayed his football career.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} Then the following year in March, South Korea's Military Manpower Administration announced that Park could delayed his military service until 2022 because of his residency in Europe.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} This lead an apology from Park, though this allowed him to participate in the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012 Olympic Games]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Arsenal's Park Chu-Young apologises for military service saga, likely to play in London Olympics|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/3800/korea/2012/06/13/3169505/arsenals-park-chu-young-apologises-for-military-service-saga|publisher=Goal.com|date=13 June 2013|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nPark was selected as an over-aged player by the [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korea under-23]] manager [[Hong Myung-bo]] for the 2012 Olympic Games.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} Park scored the opening goal in the second group stage match against [[Switzerland national under-23 football team|Switzerland]].{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} In the bronze Medal match against [[Japan national under-23 football team|Japan]], Park scored the first goal in a 2\u20130 victory against their [[Japan\u2013South Korea football rivalry|rivals]].{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===2014 FIFA World Cup===\nDespite not playing regular first-team football for several years, Park was included in the South Korea national squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=World Cup news: Arsenal striker Park Chu-young makes South Korean squad|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/17247/8917003/south-korea-coach-warns-striker-park-chu-young-to-leave-arsenal|publisher=Sky Sports|date=11 May 2014|accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref> He played in the matches against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]]. His performances were heavily criticized, particularly because he registered no shots on target in either match. He was replaced by [[Kim Shin-wook]] for the team's final match against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]]. However, it was later revealed that the manager of the team, [[Hong Myung-bo]], told him not to take shots but to open up space for offensive midfielders and make runs to score. Ultimately South Korea performed poorly, and star players [[Koo Ja-cheol]] and [[Son Heung-min]] particularly did not perform well in the manager's set-up.{{Citation needed|date = November 2015}}\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 18 February 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/chu-young-park/457/|title=Park Chu-young |publisher=Soccerway.com|accessdate=2 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!-- NOTE: when updating stats, update the infobox too! -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\" valign=\"center\"|[[FC Seoul]]\n|[[K-League 2005|2005]]||[[K League]]\n|19||12||2||0||11||6||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||18\n|-\n|[[2006 K League|2006]]||K League\n|26||7||2||2||4||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||10\n|-\n|[[2007 K League|2007]]||K League\n|11||2||1||0||3||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||15||5\n|-\n|[[2008 K League|2008]]||K League\n|13||2||0||0||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||17||2\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total\n!69!!23!!5!!2!!22!!10!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!96!!35\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]\n|[[2008\u201309 Ligue 1|2008\u201309]]||[[Ligue 1]]\n|31||5||3||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||5\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Ligue 1|2009\u201310]]||Ligue 1\n|27||8||5||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||33||9\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Ligue 1|2010\u201311]]||Ligue 1\n|33||12||0||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||12\n|-\n! colspan